<HEAD>Federal Bank Official Sought FBI Probe of Critic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> congressman says `` something just does n't smell right'' about a federal banking agency's request for an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> check of one of its critics. The request to the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> from a <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> official `` smacks of a way of life that seems to be more appropriate to life in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> than it does in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Florio </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, said Friday. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> check was revealed by an internal bank board investigation requested by <PERSON> Florio </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> consumer protection subcommittee. The report, by bank board Inspector General <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibbons </PERSON>, disclosed that the office of <PERSON> Rosemary </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>, bank board enforcement director, asked the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> on Aug. 17 to check on <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Juliano </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Laurel </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, developer. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> returned the request, which listed only <PERSON> Juliano </PERSON>'s name and address, stamped `` insufficient information,'' and Ms. <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> decided not to pursue the matter. Because of <PERSON> Juliano </PERSON>'s criticism, <PERSON> Florio </PERSON> had asked for an investigation of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Asset </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disposition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the arm of the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> that manages and sells real estate from bankrupt savings and loans. <ORGANIZATION> FADA </ORGANIZATION> was under attack from <PERSON> Juliano </PERSON>, other business people and members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for reported mismanagement and conflicts of interest. <PERSON> Juliano </PERSON> had threatened to bring a class action lawsuit against <ORGANIZATION> FADA </ORGANIZATION> on behalf of disgruntled developers who believed they had been poorly treated by the agency. Ms. <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> told investigators she was asked in June to obtain the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> check from FADA General Counsel <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Axley </PERSON>, who said <PERSON> Juliano </PERSON> had made verbal threats and written nasty letters to then <ORGANIZATION> FADA </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Rosyln </PERSON> <PERSON> Payne </PERSON>. <PERSON> Axley </PERSON> told the investigators that Ms. <PERSON> Payne </PERSON> asked him to `` have <PERSON> Juliano </PERSON> checked out'' after she received anonymous telephone calls in the middle of the night to her unlisted home telephone. <PERSON> Axley </PERSON> said he subsequently received a tip that <PERSON> Juliano </PERSON> had ties to organized crime. However, the bank board report said the tip referred to someone with a different first name than <PERSON> Juliano </PERSON>'s. After her request to the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> was returned, Ms. <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> said she learned more about the nature of <PERSON> Juliano </PERSON>'s dispute with <ORGANIZATION> FADA </ORGANIZATION>, consulted her superiors at the bank board and decided it was not appropriate for her to resubmit the query to the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>. But <PERSON> Florio </PERSON> said, `` For the bank board to even contemplate investigating a citizen for complaining raises a lot of questions. ... Something just does n't smell right here.'' Ms. <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> did not immediately return telephone messages left at her office Friday afternoon. There was no answer at <PERSON> Juliano </PERSON>'s office <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyle </PERSON>, a bank board spokesman, said the agency acknowledges that the request to the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> should never have been made. `` Once we were aware of it, we indicated we did n't want that pursued and after that it was not,'' he said. `` <PERSON> Rosemary </PERSON>, to her credit, said ` Maybe we're not supposed to be doing that sort of thing.''' The bank board has also acknowledged that a law firm hired by <ORGANIZATION> FADA </ORGANIZATION> engaged a private detective agency to look into <PERSON> Juliano </PERSON>'s finances <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> would not consider it proper to investigate a government critic. The bureau's practice, he said, is to ask for more information about the reason a background check is requested and if the explanation is not appropriate it can recommend administrative or disciplinary actions against the person who made the request. <PERSON> Hoyle </PERSON> said Ms. <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> has not been reprimanded.
