<FIRST>r a PM-HorseradishHorrors     04-02 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Horseradish Horrors,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Passover Horseradish Health Hazard Cited By Doctors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Horseradish eaten during traditional Passover dinners can pose a health hazard, says a Jewish doctor whose father collapsed after consuming an olive-sized serving of the bitter herb. Dr. <PERSON> Haya </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> said Friday that her father, <ORGANIZATION> Cleveland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> sociologist <PERSON> Israel </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON>, quickly recovered after he fainted, keeled over and suffered a small seizure during a Seder, or traditional Passover meal, several years ago. She said the incident shows that people prone to high blood pressure, heart or artery disease or stroke might be better off if they let horseradish fumes evaporate by keeping it uncovered for a half hour before the Seder, or use a substitute such as chopped romaine lettuce stalks. <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> suffered high blood pressure before the incident, said his daughter, an internist at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, and consultant to the <ORGANIZATION> Rand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The Passover holiday, which celebrates the Israelites' Exodus from slavery in ancient <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, extends from Friday night until sundown April 9. Seders are held on the first two nights. Horseradish is eaten during the ceremonial meal as a `` bitter herb'' symbolizing the bitterness of slavery. A letter warning that horseradish can be dangerous was published Friday in the Journal of the American Medical Association by Ms. <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> and Dr. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wu </PERSON>, a clinical instructor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Wu </PERSON> said the horseradish-induced sudden loss of blood pressure that caused <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> to faint and collapse could trigger a fatal stroke, heart attack or abnormal heart rhythm in people with heart disease. <PERSON> Wu </PERSON> and Ms. <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> trained together at <ORGANIZATION> Mount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sinai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. They decided to write the letter after <PERSON> Wu </PERSON> spotted a letter about a similar incident published in the same journal in January. In that letter, Dr. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Spitzer </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Montefiore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> told how a healthy 63-year-old man collapsed after eating a large mound of wasabi, or green-colored Japanese horseradish, during a meal of sushi. <PERSON> Spitzer </PERSON>'s letter was headlined: `` Horseradish Horrors: Sushi Syncope.'' <PERSON> Syncope </PERSON> means fainting. The follow-up letter by Ms. <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Wu </PERSON> carried the headline `` The Bitter Herbs of Seder: More on Horseradish Horrors.'' Ms. <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> said horseradish usually is grated. But the night her father collapsed, the family ground it in a food processor, then placed it in an airtight container, preventing vapors from escaping and making the horseradish unusually potent. <PERSON> Wu </PERSON> said the collapse probably occurred because the horseradish vapors caused a reflexive drop in blood pressure. Coupled with the elder <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON>'s consumption of Passover wine and use of medicine to reduce his high blood pressure, that briefly deprived the brain of enough blood. `` He still eats horseradish,'' Ms. <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> said. `` My dad is sort of macho.''
