<SECOND>AM-Hash Bash,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>400 Get High On Pot Reform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 400 people huffed and puffed Friday at the 17th annual Hash Bash, a spring rally for the legalization of marijuana. Police made no arrests and issued no citations during the event on the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> campus. University officials had issued a permit for the event but emphasized they were not endorsing it. Possession of small amounts of marijuana in <LOCATION> Ann </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arbor </LOCATION> is punishable by a $ 5 fine. `` I've been coming to this since I was a little boy,'' said a 29-year-old who called himself Jizmo Noodles and was one of the first to light up. `` My first one was in 1973. It's a means of expression, civil disobedience.'' Noodles, carrying incense and wearing jeans, a T-shirt and a denim vest with a peace sign, described himself as a `` student of life.'' <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Gettman </PERSON>, assistant director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> for the Reform of Marijuana Laws, or <ORGANIZATION> NORML </ORGANIZATION>, told the gathering that pot smokers were tired of being labeled criminals. `` We're here for a lot of different reasons today,'' he said. `` A lot of people think that because this is April Fools' Day, that this is some some kind of a joke. We are serious, very serious.'' <ORGANIZATION> NORML </ORGANIZATION> wants marijuana legalized, with taxes on it used to develop treatment centers for cocaine and heroin users. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Amicone </PERSON>, sophomore history major, said he started smoking marijuana at 16. `` I got a late start,'' he said.
