<HEAD>Jailed Opposition Leader Called ``Hostage''; U.S. Boosts Military
Presence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soldiers were off the streets as Easter weekend began and a jailed opposition leader's wife said her husband was being held hostage in Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s effort to maintain power Also Friday, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said it was sending 1,300 more military personnel to protect <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bases and thousands of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> residents, bringing to nearly 12,000 the number of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. Opposition leaders said they planned to meet today or Sunday to decide whether to lift a 12-day-old general strike that has shut down most commercial activity in an effort to oust <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s de facto leader and heads of its 15,000-member <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION>. Virtually all businesses were closed for Good Friday. The general strike had eased earlier in the week, with groceries and pharmacies reopening, reportedly under government pressure. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, news reports said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration officials had discussed trying to force <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> from power through military intervention, kidnapping or by arranging a coup. The general is under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> indictment on drug trafficking charges. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Lastra </PERSON>, a top leader of the opposition National Civic Crusade, spent his fifth day in jail Friday. Other Crusade leaders and several journalists arrested with him Monday had all been released by midday Tuesday. `` All legal efforts on his behalf have been useless,'' <PERSON> Vilma </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Lastra </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATI