<HEAD>Magazine Helps Reunite Americans Whose Schools Were Far From Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Overseas Brats, a magazine for Americans who went to high school half a world away from their homeland, is helping them find classmates they have n't seen for years, says its Army brat publisher. `` The difference between stateside graduates and <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> brats, <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> brats, <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> juniors and others is that those in stateside have a hometown to go to for a reunion,'' said publisher and editor <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Condrill </PERSON>. `` But the brats, after they graduate, they leave the military environment and sometimes are lost,'' he said. Military dependents often are seen as pampered kids living off their globe-traveling parents, <PERSON> Condrill </PERSON> said recently. But they endure hardships abroad and often have trouble adjusting to American life, he said. Class reunions help by bringing overseas graduates together, he said. `` These people need someone who understands their predicament,'' said <PERSON> Condrill </PERSON>, 32. At least 1 million people have gone to overseas <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> schools since the institutions were created in 1946, <PERSON> Condrill </PERSON> said. More than 80,000 students attend overseas schools each year and more than 5,000 graduate. `` We're not going to find everybody through the magazine, but at least this is one way of finding some of them,'' said <PERSON> Condrill </PERSON>, whose father was an Army colonel. <PERSON> Condrill </PERSON>, a 1973 graduate of the <ORGANIZATION> Tehran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, said many military dependents are unable to have 10-year high school reunions like graduates of stateside schools because their classes usually are so small. Some can not return to their alma maters because it would be too expensive. Because of the difficulty in organizing reunions, many students who attended a particular overseas school get together, even if they graduated in different years. `` These reunions create incredible bonds,'' <PERSON> Condrill </PERSON> said. `` When you put these people together I'm not surprised to see strangers talking like old friends.'' <PERSON> Condrill </PERSON>, who founded his quarterly magazine in 1986, boasts 1,000 subscribers in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and 12 countries. During the day he works for a floor products company, but spends evenings and weekends answering correspondence or writing stories for Overseas Brats. His byline appears on most stories, but there are a few subscribers who offer articles reminiscing about growing up overseas. The 12-page tabloid also carries announcements about upcoming reunions and personal advertisements that resemble lost-and-found ads. <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Roth </PERSON>, a 1976 graduate of <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dewey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Subic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, organized a reunion in 1986 before the magazine was founded. She says the magazine has made finding friends much easier today. `` Overseas Brats has been a big help,'' said the <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, woman. `` It's interesting reading other people's experiences, and it has made me realize that we are a unique group, sort of a loose fraternity It has helped us unite.'' <PERSON> Condrill </PERSON> also has helped organize reunions. In 1982, only six overseas schools held reunions, but 30 three-day reunions are planned this summer throughout the country, <PERSON> Condrill </PERSON> said. `` This takes them back to a happier time, to a more innocent time in their lives,'' he said. `` At these things they are not talking about kids, about taxes. They feel much younger than they are and they're talking with people who were in the same predicament as they were.''
