<HEAD>Gandhi Urged To Declare Emergency; 14 More Slain As Security
Stepped Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leaders in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> called on Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> to impose a state of emergency in their northern state to quell violence by <ORGANIZATION> Sikh </ORGANIZATION> separatists that has killed more than 100 people this week. Late Friday and early today, Sikh extremists killed 14 more people in the <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state as police stepped up security on <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s orders, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> reported. The prime minister also called the federally appointed <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> governor, <ORGANIZATION> S.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ray </ORGANIZATION>, to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> today for urgent consultations on the violence. In addition, police and paramilitary troops began stepping up security on <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>' border with the state, where police say smugglers have been moving large quantities of new weapons to the Sikh extremists, <ORGANIZATION> UNI </ORGANIZATION> said. The latest killings raised to 111 the number of people who have died in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> since Sunday in attacks blamed on militant Sikhs who have since 1982 been waging a guerrilla war for a separate homeland. So far this year, more than 635 people have died in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state, including Hindus and moderate Sikhs. Sikh militants say they are discriminated against by <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s Hindu majority. Right-wing Hindu groups called for a general strike in <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> District today to protest the killings. Residents of the Sikh holy city of <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> said about half of the city's shops were shuttered today, but government offices and schools remained open and transportion was normal. <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> leaders of <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> called Friday for the state of emergency. They included <PERSON> Bhagwan </PERSON> <PERSON> Dass </PERSON>, vice president of the state <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s governing committee, two of the state party's general secretaries and a former president. The federal government last month was empowered by Parliament to impose an emergency in a single state to combat `` internal disturbances.'' Under an emergency, the government would have the authority to detain people without warrants, suspend press freedom and take other steps against the militants. Sikhs, whose religion was formed about 500 years ago as an alternative to <LOCATION> Hinduism </LOCATION> and Islam, make up less than 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s population of 800 million but are in a majority in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> UNI </ORGANIZATION> said that eight Sikhs, four Hindus and two unidentified people were killed overnight in three districts of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> by suspected Sikh gunmen. Thirty-seven people were reported killed Thursday night and Friday in the state, the worst one-day toll since March 4, when 45 people were reported slain in a single day, 34 of them at a festival marking the Indian holiday of Holi.
