<HEAD>Human-Powered Flight Called Off At Last Moment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HERAKLION, Crete (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Breezy weather early today forced organizers to scratch their attempt at a world-record human-powered flight across the <LOCATION> Aegean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> by a cyclist-pilot in a flying machine called the Daedalus. Windless weather is important for the 74-mile flight to the island of <LOCATION> Santorini </LOCATION> and winds of nearly six miles an hour grounded the silver-and-pink aircraft on a military runway at the last moment. `` It's disappointing, but the wind seems to be a little too strong,'' pilot <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Zack </PERSON>, 26, a professional cyclist from <LOCATION> Wilmington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, told reporters. The last-minute postponement illustrated just how unpredictable the weather can be on this southern Greek island. Gusting winds and rain squalls delayed the first scheduled flight of the <ORGANIZATION> Daedalus </ORGANIZATION> 88 on Wednesday. After nine days of blustery weather, conditions Thursday were good enough to allow the five athlete pilots to take turns test-flying the plane at speeds of around 14 miles per hour and about 15 feet above the tarmac of the <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> air force base. A successful touchdown on <LOCATION> Santorini </LOCATION> -LRB- Thira -RRB- would more than triple the exisiting record of 22.5 miles for straight-line human-powered flight, set by <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> piloting the Gossamer Albatross across the English channel in 1979. Built of high-tech composite materials _ graphite epoxy, kevlar plastic fiber and mylar polystyrene film _ the <ORGANIZATION> Daedalus </ORGANIZATION> plane has a huge 112-foot wingspan and resembles an outsized insect in flight. The flight in a fragile pedal-powered plane is aimed at emulating <ORGANIZATION> Daedalus </ORGANIZATION>, the legendary craftsman who flapped his way across the <LOCATION> Aegean </LOCATION> on wings of wax and feathers, according to a 3,500-year-old Greek myth. According to the myth, <ORGANIZATION> Daedalus </ORGANIZATION> made it safely across the <LOCATION> Aegean </LOCATION> but his son <PERSON> Icarus </PERSON> flew too close to the sun and plummeted to his death as his wings melted.
