<HEAD>Colonel Who Led Bloody Challenge To Aquino Escapes Custody</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Aquino saying Honasan was about to
be court-martialed, tight guard at presidential palace, details on
escape. EDITS to tighten. No pickup.
^LaserPhoto NY74</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The young officer who led an August coup attempt that nearly felled President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s government fled a prison ship in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> early today aided by his elite navy guards Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> cut short a private Easter holiday in northern <LOCATION> Luzon </LOCATION> and rushed to the capital for an emergency Cabinet meeting after hearing of the escape of former Lt. Col. <PERSON> Gregorio </PERSON> `` Gringo'' <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON>. She told a national television audience <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON> was to have been court-martialed for leading the bloody Aug. 28 coup attempt, in which at least 53 people were killed and hundreds wounded. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> warned military personnel that those who assist or harbor <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON> `` will be dealt with promptly and severely with the full force of the law.'' The charismatic soldier escaped at about 2:30 a.m. aboard two rubber boats along with 14 guards from the <ORGANIZATION> navy </ORGANIZATION>'s Special Warfare Unit who were guarding him, Col. <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Florendo </PERSON>, chief military spokesman, told reporters. <PERSON> Florendo </PERSON> said the roughly half dozen remaining guards fired on the boats as they slipped away in the darkness, but apparently missed. The prison ship, the <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonifacio </PERSON>, was anchored 500 yards from the <ORGANIZATION> navy </ORGANIZATION>'s main wharf, he said. Chief of Staff Gen. <PERSON> Renato </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Villa </PERSON> ordered a nationwide search for the 39-year-old <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON>, who had been on the ship since his December arrest in a <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> suburb. Armored personnel carriers and bulldozers blocked entrances to military camps in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>, and checkpoints were set up on major highways. <PERSON> Florendo </PERSON> said a reserve lieutenant who was frustrated over his inability to obtain a regular commission had aided in the escape. `` It is believed that bribery was a factor,'' the spokesman added, saying the lieutenant and 13 enlisted personnel had apparently assisted and joined in the escape. He said the boats used to flee had been sent to increase security after the military learned of a plot to free <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON>. <PERSON> Florendo </PERSON> warned that <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON> may try to organize a new bid to topple Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>. He said the government expected <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON> to resume anti-Aquino propaganda efforts and again try to divide the military. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> said <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON> fled to avoid prosecution for mutiny and sedition, arson, murder and conduct unbecoming an officer. She said his escape `` is tantamount to an admission of his guilt.'' She also said <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON> staged his coup attempt to evade investigation of alleged misapproriation of $ 100,000 worth of military equipment and to avoid a combat assignment against communist rebels. `` I appeal to all citizens and leaders, public and private, to assist us in the recapture of <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON> as soon as possible,'' she said. Presidential guards stepped up security around the presidential palace immediately after word of the escape. Civilians were barred from the palace compound. <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON> said the military was `` taking every possible action'' to bring back <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON> and `` minimize or neutralize any further damage that he can make.'' <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON>, former <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> chief of security, played a key role in the Feb. 22, 1986 mutiny that with a popular uprising toppled President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>. But he became disillusioned with Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>, accusing her of `` weak and inept'' leadership that fortified the 19-year-old communist insurgency. On Aug. 28, <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON> led a force of 2,000 men who attacked the presidential palace and seized several media and military installations in the capital before they were driven off by pro-Aquino forces. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> said the attack it was aimed at killing her and her family. <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON>'s was the most serious of several major plots to unseat Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>. The military says 11 officers and 90 enlisted men involved in the coup attempt are still at large. <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON> is widely regarded within the 160,000-member armed forces as a courageous, experienced officer. Military sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said he is so popular he had become the `` dominant figure'' aboard the ship that was supposed to be his prison. <PERSON> Florendo </PERSON> said the military received information a week ago that <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON> would try to escape and it sent rubber boats to guard the ship, expecting outsiders to try to storm the vessel. `` Instead, it came from the inside.'' <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON> was <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> security chief when opposition Sen. <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ponce </PERSON> <PERSON> Enrile </PERSON> was minister of national defense. <PERSON> Enrile </PERSON> was fired in November 1986 after the government said it thwarted a coup attempt by his followers. <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON> remained in hiding for months after the August coup. Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Ramon </PERSON> <PERSON> Montano </PERSON>, former commander of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>, said weeks before the arrest that <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON> was being protected by undisclosed civilian and military figures.
