<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A disc jockey who told a white lie about the weather found his listeners ready for an April Fools' Day snow job. WKIR-FM radio personality <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Baxter </PERSON> told a whopper about the weather that was swallowed hook, line and sinker by some listeners. His phony forecast _ freezing rain and snow _ in a state where the merest hint of winter weather sends residents scurrying to the grocery put a damper on at least one businessman's day. `` They said the rain was supposed to turn to sleet and snow, and the temperature tonight and tomorrow was going to be in the 20s,'' said barber <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON>, who said trade was slow following <PERSON> Baxter </PERSON>'s bogus prediction of icy streets `` I'm not going to listen to that station any more,'' <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> said. The state <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patrol </ORGANIZATION> was bombarded with anxious calls about road conditions. Troopers were stymied, however, when they turned to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> for help. `` The weather service called us wanting to know where we got our information,'' station spokeswoman <PERSON> Rhonda </PERSON> <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> said. `` Then the Highway Patrol called wanting to talk to the station manager. Then, the Civil Defense called wanting to talk to the station manager.'' <PERSON> Baxter </PERSON> went on air to apologize, and told listeners he'd lost his job. April Fool! `` He's still kidding around,'' <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> said. `` The phone has n't stopped ringing -LRB- with listeners concerned for <PERSON> Baxter </PERSON> -RRB- since I got in,'' said <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, the disc jockey who follows <PERSON> Baxter </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A disc jockey's on-air account of an unidentified flying object causing commotion in a park was so convincing that some people claimed they witnessed the mysterious rumble and flash of light. `` People are seeing it. But it ai n't there,'' said <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Honsberger </PERSON>, news director for KDKA-AM, the station that broadcast the April Fools' Day joke. `` We just had a lady call who said she saw a bunch of gray trucks go in led by a jeep. These people are claiming to have seen that thing. But we started it all,'' <PERSON> Honsberger </PERSON> said, chuckling. Not everyone was laughing. Worried listeners flooded the switchboard at the <LOCATION> Allegheny </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> police station in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>. Sgt. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolverton </PERSON> repeatedly assured callers there was nothing going on and that the radio report had been a hoax. `` They were pretty much upset with the fact that a radio station would be allowed to get away it,'' <PERSON> Wolverton </PERSON> said. `` A lot of them were critical because they picked Good Friday. Good Friday seemed to be more important than April Fools' Day.'' Morning disc jockey <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Cigna </PERSON> startled his listeners with the report and offered no explanation or elaboration when he ended his four-hour broadcast at 9 a.m. But his replacement, <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawkes </PERSON>, informed listeners it had been a joke. `` Remember everyone, today is April Fools' Day,'' <PERSON> Hawkes </PERSON> said. None of the morning news reports included the so-called emergency, <PERSON> Honsberger </PERSON> noted. `` That should be a clue to anybody,'' he said. `` If anything was happening, it would be our lead story. We'd have reporters there.''
