<HEAD>Tornadoes Damage Parts Of East Texas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUND CITY, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tornadoes touched down in five east <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> towns, destroying two mobiles homes, damaging dozens of houses and overturning cars, authorities said. One minor injury was reported. In East Mountain, near <LOCATION> Longview </LOCATION>, a tornado damaged 25 homes Friday, blowing seven or eight of them off their foundations, witnesses said. `` I was on top of the mountain watching for tails out of the clouds when the rain began falling so hard you could n't even see,'' said East Mountain Assistant City Marshal <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Luchau </PERSON>. `` We knew the storm was getting worse, but it happened so quick, there was n't time to warn anyone. A tornado also destroyed two mobile homes and damaged three homes in nearby Glenwood Acres, officials said, but it was unclear whether it was the same tornado that struck East Mountain. The city hall, an elementary school and a car dealership suffered heavy damage at <LOCATION> Gladewater </LOCATION>, about 20 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Longview </LOCATION>. A supermarket and several mobile homes also were hit. Another tornado damaged four homes in <LOCATION> Mound </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, and severely damaged the <LOCATION> Mound </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Store </LOCATION>. `` It just has n't sunk in yet,'' said <PERSON> Deanna </PERSON> <PERSON> Holden </PERSON>, owner of the store. `` We just all got underneath the dining room table. If we had n't gotten my grandbaby out of her crib, she'd be dead because of all the flying glass.'' <PERSON> Shan </PERSON> <PERSON> Haggerty </PERSON>, 10, of <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> was cut on the hand by flying glass as he crouched beneath a kitchen table of a <LOCATION> Mound </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> home he was visiting. A tornado also was spotted in <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grove </LOCATION>, where strong winds destroyed one home and damaged at least one other. At least four tornadoes hit <LOCATION> Anderson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> in 1987, killing two people. Three of them hit the southern part of the county, near <LOCATION> Mound </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. `` This is a bad area for tornadoes,'' said <PERSON> Tommie </PERSON> <PERSON> Denson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Mound </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. `` We're going to move. I'm going to sell my home and leave.''
