<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> said today that its forces have overrun Kurdish guerrilla bases in the mountainous northeast in an offensive aimed at crushing Iranian-backed rebels who threaten vital oilfields. Kurdish guerrilla leaders have claimed the Iraqis, backed by tanks and air strikes, were dropping poison gas bombs on villages in what one commander called `` a war of genocide.'' <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> Radio, monitored in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>, quoted a military communique as saying its troops `` completely purged'' the area around <LOCATION> Qara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dagh </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Sulaimaniyeh </LOCATION> region, 50 miles west of the <LOCATION> Kirkuk </LOCATION> oilfields. <PERSON> Qara </PERSON> <PERSON> Dagh </PERSON> is only 20 miles west of <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Darbandikhan </LOCATION>, where Iranian Revolutionary Guards have thrust into <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> in a 16-day-old offensive. `` All traitors have finally been destroyed,'' the communique declared in a reference to the Iranian-backed Kurdish rebels who have been fighting <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> for an independent homeland for years. There was no independent confirmation. <PERSON> Jalal </PERSON> <PERSON> Talabani </PERSON>, leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Patriotic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kurdistan </ORGANIZATION>, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that heavy fighting was raging in the region Friday but that he had no reports of an Iraqi breakthrough. <PERSON> Massud </PERSON> <PERSON> Barzani </PERSON>, leader of the Iranian-backed <ORGANIZATION> Kurdish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said in a statement several days ago, that the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> army had launched a major offensive against the guerrillas March 23. He said two divisions of troops, backed by tanks, artillery and air strikes, were seeking to dislodge Kurdish fighters from the <LOCATION> Qara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dagh </LOCATION> mountains between <LOCATION> Kirkuk </LOCATION> and the provincial capital of <LOCATION> Sulaimaniyeh </LOCATION>. An Iraqi division usually numbers about 12,000 men. <PERSON> Barzani </PERSON> said the Iraqi assaults had been beaten back. He claimed Iraqi warplanes were dropping chemical bombs on Kurdish strongholds and villages suspected of harboring guerrillas. The villages were north of the <LOCATION> Iranian </LOCATION> bridgehead around <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Darbandikhan </LOCATION>, where <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> claims Iraqi chemical bombing attacks March 16-17 killed 5,000 civilians and injured as many more. <PERSON> Talabani </PERSON> said the Iraqis had seized some villages. He also charged the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> air force was dropping gas bombs on Kurdish settlements. `` It's a war of genocide against the Kurdish people,'' he said in a telephone interview. `` They use chemical weapons against us all the time and raze our villages.'' Today's communique said an <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> force, including Kurdish fighters loyal to <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>, had overrun 21 Kurdish bases and villages used by the guerrillas in the last few days. It gave no casualty figure. The Kurdish guerrillas have in the last 18 months created a second front in the 7 -LCB- - year-old Iran-Iraq war The Iraqis have had to divert tens of thousands of troops badly needed in the main battle zones in the south to contain the insurgency in <LOCATION> Kurdistan </LOCATION>. The Kurds claimed to control 4,000 square miles in the northeast. About 20 million Kurds live in the mountainous region where the borders of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> meet.
