<HEAD>Huge Price Hikes Take Effect; Government Troops Kill 38 Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Marxist government imposed huge price inceases on food, and a government newspaper said Saturday that the increases were necessitated by a guerrilla war that has ravaged the economy. Prices for rice, sugar, corn, cooking oil, bread and soap all rose sharply under government-mandated increases that took effect Friday in the southern African nation. In a bid to offset the higher food prices, the government also granted wage increases to some workers. <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> went from 9 cents to 60 cents per kilogram, about 2.2 pounds. Corn flour rose from nine cents to 32 cents per kilogram and a kilogram of sugar went from 11 cents to 59 cents. The minimum wage for an industrial worker has been raised from about $ 17 a month to $ 29 per month. However, raises were not granted to workers in factories that were losing money. <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> also has a high unemployment rate and thousands of refugees displaced by a war raging since the 1960s. <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> won independence from <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> in 1975 after years of fighting. Since then guerrillas of the <ORGANIZATION> Mozambique </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resistance </ORGANIZATION> have been battling to oust the Marxist government. The daily newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Noticias </ORGANIZATION>, in an editorial Saturday, blamed the country's economic woes on `` the continued and systematic aggression against <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>, carried out by the racist regimes of the region _ first <LOCATION> Rhodesia </LOCATION> and later <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>.'' In the mid-1970s, then white-ruled <LOCATION> Rhodesia </LOCATION> helped backed the anti-Marxist guerrillas. After <LOCATION> Rhodesia </LOCATION> became black-ruled <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> in 1980, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> began supplying the rebels. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> signed a mutual non-aggression pact in 1984, but both sides regularly accuse the other of violations. <PERSON> Noticias </PERSON> said foreign support of the rebels has destabilized <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> and `` has prevented us from consolidating our independence and developing our economy.'' `` <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>, devastated by more than 20 consecutive years of war, is currently one of the poorest countries in the world,'' Noticias said. `` The state can no longer go on paying food subsidies.'' An estimated 5 million of <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>'s 14.5 million people are in need of food aid. In other developments, government troops killed 38 rebel fighters in clashes during the past week in three separate provinces, the national news agency AIM said. The rebels were killed in clashes from March 29-31 in the central provinces of <LOCATION> Sofala </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Zambazia </LOCATION> and the northwestern province of Tete, AIM said, citing a report on Radio <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>. The report made no mention of government troop casualties.
