 President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> and politicians from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s left and right put aside their quarrels Saturday and paid their last respects to <PERSON> Edgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Faure </PERSON>, one of the most widely respected statesmen of the century. <PERSON> Faure </PERSON>, a brilliant and witty politician who in four decades of service occupied nearly every important French government post except president, died Wednesday at the age of 79. The ceremony at <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>' St. <PERSON> Clotilde </PERSON> <PERSON> Basilica </PERSON> was simple. <PERSON> Faure </PERSON>'s plain coffin was draped with the French Tricolor Upon it was placed the bicorn hat and sword of the <ORGANIZATION> Academie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francaise </ORGANIZATION>, of which he was a member. Mgr. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Pezeril </PERSON>, former auxiliary bishop of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, represented Cardinal <PERSON> Jean-Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Lustiger </PERSON> in conducting the service. In his brief homily, <PERSON> Pezeril </PERSON> noted <PERSON> Faure </PERSON>'s long fight for human rights, saying he believed such a fight was a `` touchstone of political responsibility.'' `` As a Christian, the deceased will have thus participated in the fate of the world,'' he said. Also attending were <PERSON> Bernadette </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, representing her husband, Premier <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, who was on a trip to the <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antilles </LOCATION>; former President <PERSON> Valery </PERSON> <PERSON> Giscard </PERSON> d'Estaing; <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaban-Delmas </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Alain </PERSON> <PERSON> Poher </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>; Finance Minister <PERSON> 