<FIRST>r w AM-Trade Bjt   04-02 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trade, Bjt,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Bucks for Corn and Bean Research Snag Trade Measure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Efforts to wrap up farm provisions of the 1,000-page trade bill are snagged over a plan by Sen. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Harkin </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Iowa </LOCATION>, to pump $ 75 million a year into crop research every year for 20 years. The plan is designed principally to spur demand for corn and soybeans by finding new, non-food uses for them, leading to higher farm earnings. `` It's really a long-term agricultural bill, an investment in the future,'' press secretary <PERSON> Pam </PERSON> <PERSON> McKinney </PERSON> says. Thus far, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> negotiators on the trade bill are n't so sure. The plan would be a boon for <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and similar research centers but could whet other lawmakers' appetites for more of the same for the folks back in their own states. The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, E. `` Kika'' de la <PERSON> Garza </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, has been cool toward the notion thus far. And for that reason farm lawmakers were still wrangling late in the week, when most other conferees on the trade bill had reached tentative agreement. It now appears unlikely that the matter will be resolved until after April 11, when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> returns from its spring break. As big as it is, the plant research provision is small potatoes compared to some of the subsidy programs that do have tentative approval from the trade conferees. Chief among them is a so-called `` triggered marketing loan'' program, similar to export subsidies contained in the 1985 farm law, that sent <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cotton and rice exports skyrocketing _ but at a hefty price to taxpayers. The latest proposal focuses on the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's goal of using the current <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> Round of trade talks to start the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and its trading partners on a course of phasing out all agricultural subsidies. Failure to make `` substantial progress'' on such an agreement by 1990 would trigger the estimated $ 500 million marketing loan program designed to boost exports of wheat, feed grains and oilseed crops. Soybean farmers have been clamoring for a marketing loan program, under which producers receive price-support loans from the government as usual, pay them off at the lower, world price of the crop and pocket the difference. Even if Uruguay Round talks bogged down, the next president could refuse to put the 1990 marketing loan into effect if he were prepared to assure <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that the subsidy program would would harm the international negotiations. Doing that, however, would trigger one of the trade package's most expensive and complex features _ an offshoot of the 1985 Export Enhancement Program, which has sent millions of dollars in government-owned surplus crops to private exporters Big grain companies and other exporting firms receive the surplus crops as bonuses to spur overseas shipments of American farm products. The program remains in effect and the trade proposal would extend it through 1990 and boost the price tag from $ 1.5 billion to $ 2.5 billion. A presidential waiver of the marketing loan would automatically trigger a new export program, requiring the government to pay out no less than $ 2 billion in additional surplus-crop bonuses. These bonuses represent a heavy cost to taxpayers because the commodities were acquired mainly through unredeemed price-support loans to farmers.
