<SECOND>AM-Time Changes,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time Change Means More Than Lost Hour Of Sleep</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH HARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When the clock jumps forward an hour for daylight-saving time at 2 a.m. Sunday morning, it means a little more than a lost hour of sleep. `` People's stomachs will be telling them ` Snickers bar' and we'll be serving lunch. But if you're an early eater, it'll be beneficial,'' said <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Manzer </PERSON>, manager of the <ORGANIZATION> Chattanooga </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Riverboat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>. The firm plans to serve an Easter brunch on the <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> river Sunday afternoon, but the time change `` will probably affect people's appetites,'' said <PERSON> Manzer </PERSON>. Businesses and services that work on into the night lost an hour _ or gained an hour, depending on the point of view. Some police officers who work the night shift get to go home an hour early. They do n't lose an hour's pay for their `` early'' departure. And when the time changes back in the fall, they'll get an hour's overtime pay, officials said Friday. Firefighters who work 24-hour shifts are in the same situation. Some churches will hold additional services for sleepyheads and for the holiday crowds. Going visiting for Easter? The nation's public transportation system is ready for the switch, said <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Waymack </PERSON>, manager of a <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> travel agency. `` At some points there are some minor changes in schedules, but for most airlines, cruise ships and trains, it's just another day on the job,'' <PERSON> Waymack </PERSON> said. Most of the schedule changes come about because of the season, not daylight-saving time, he said. Some flight times might be adjusted one or two minutes because of changes in headwinds, <PERSON> Waymack </PERSON> said, and others might be changed to accommodate peak passenger loads. `` It's really a very sophisticated system,'' <PERSON> Waymack </PERSON> said. `` They've had a number of years since the <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> brothers to perfect it.'' But he urged passengers to double-check departures 24 hours in advance. At <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tennessee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, spokesman <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said the time change would have little effect on most banking services. However, he said, there might be a moment's hesitation when computer operators key in the commands to switch times on the banking computers, automated tellers and other equipment. `` It just depends on how quickly an operator can enter it in,'' <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said. Recorded time and temperature announcements must be changed, along with signs at banks, shopping malls and stores. <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Birdsong </PERSON>, assistant to the general manager at <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>'s WYHY-FM, said she will have to come to the station at 2 a.m. Sunday morning to make the change in the time and temperature announcement computer. Bank and store signs are also changed by computer, usually by the owner of the sign, said <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Allison </PERSON>, owner of <PERSON> Allison </PERSON> <PERSON> Sales </PERSON> and Marketing. `` The time works off an internal clock, which you reset just as you would a digital clock,'' <PERSON> Allison </PERSON> said. Time clocks must also be changed before workers punch in Monday morning. Most computerized time clocks will make the change automatically, but there will still be thousands of older models that need to be changed by hand, said <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> technician <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Asplint </PERSON>. `` We could be doing daylight-saving time changes for the next two weeks,'' he said. This is the second year that daylight-saving time will begin on the first Sunday in April. Before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> changed the law, the time switch occurred on the last Sunday of April.
</TEXT>
