<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Armenia,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official, Dissident Sources Say Ethnic Situation Quieter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Strikes, demonstrations and tensions between national groups in two southern Soviet republics have quieted but economic damage from the unrest is severe, newspapers reported Saturday. Official and dissident sources said the atmosphere in the republics of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> was improving. But in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, activist <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON> said ethnic relations remained volatile. At a news conference at his north <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> apartment, the half-Armenian former political prisoner said he had spoken with sources in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> who told him tensions have eased there and in the disputed region of <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> in neighboring <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. However, he said he was told some residents of <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>'s main city, remained on strike. Armenian activists want <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, which is mostly Armenian, annexed to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. At least 32 people have died in ethnic violence in the region since late February in bloody clashes between Azeris and Armenians. <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION> airport had been reopened for local residents but that frequent document checks were being made at all roads leading into the region to keep outsiders away. Workers in <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION>, angered over the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>'s failure to issue a clear decision on appeals to annex the region, have been staying home for more than a week. Official newspapers acknowledged labor unrest continued, but said more people have been showing up for work. In the beginning, virtually the entire adult population went out on strike. The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper Pravda carried an interview with Armenian scholar <PERSON> Gevorg </PERSON> <PERSON> Garibdzhanyan </PERSON>, who accused the state-run press of telling a one-sided story about the <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> situation and being too quick to label Armenian activists as extremists. But he also defended the presence of Soviet troops in the Armenian capital of <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, saying he `` slept peacefully knowing our soldiers were in the city.'' It appeared from his comments that the armed security troops that patrolled the city last month had been reduced. Foreign reporters have been barred from traveling to the <LOCATION> Caucasus </LOCATION> region and telephone contact with the area has been disrupted. The national television news program <ORGANIZATION> Vremya </ORGANIZATION> reported Friday that public transport and many major industries in <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION> had been idled by the strikes and urged residents of the area to go back to work. The daily <ORGANIZATION> Sovietskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rossiya </ORGANIZATION> said Saturday that some workers showed up at major enterprises in the city of <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION> on Friday for the first time in more than a week, although the factories were still not up to full strength. An editor who answered the telephone at the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Karabakh </LOCATION> newspaper in <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION> on Saturday said the labor situation was returning to normal in the city, but declined to give his name or details. <PERSON> Selskaya </PERSON> <PERSON> Zhizn </PERSON> newspaper wrote that state and collective farms in the troubled region had lost nearly $ 775,000 by mid-March because of strikes and demonstrations. Shortages of meat, milk and eggs have resulted, the newspaper said. Even larger losses have been reported in recent days due to the industrial strikes in <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION>, where production and deliveries ground to a halt over the past week. <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> has been part of the <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> republic since 1923, although more than three-quarters of the region's 160,000 residents are Armenians. Armenians are predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION>, while most Azeris are Shiite Moslems. The labor situation worsened in <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION> in mid-March, when the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> leadership called Armenian agitation for <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>'s annexation `` intolerable.'' While apparently rejecting the bid for reuniting the region with <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, the party and government leadership unveiled a program to invest $ 690 million in housing and social services like Armenian-language schools, literature and broadcasting.
