<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Roland </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickey </PERSON> once again is ready to don a rabbit costume and take some holiday cheer to area hospitals in his annual spring role as the `` ether bunny.'' <PERSON> Dickey </PERSON>, 73, first put on the fuzzy suit and long ears when fellow members of the <ORGANIZATION> Loyal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Order </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moose </ORGANIZATION> asked him to preside over the club's annual Easter egg hunt. `` Then I got the idea that I would like to expand and bring the bunny into the children's hospital wards,'' <PERSON> Dickey </PERSON> said. Nurses dubbed him the `` ether bunny'' many years ago after he fainted on the bunny trail, he said. `` I was at <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, walking back to the children's wards, when I walked past one of the operating rooms,'' <PERSON> Dickey </PERSON> said `` Back in those days, they used ether as anesthetic. The ether got trapped up in that bunny head and out I went.'' After doing his routine for 41 years, <PERSON> Dickey </PERSON> said he has no plans to retire. `` Everybody asks me, ` When are you going to get someone else to do it?' I want to keep doing it for as long as I can,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mr. <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> was n't taking calls at the <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> Zoo Friday. Neither did <PERSON> Buffy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Katz </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Boon </PERSON>, <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Key </PERSON> or P.N. <PERSON> Gwynne </PERSON>. But that did n't stop many April Fools' targets from trying to return calls to those characters. `` They's groaners, I'm telling you,'' <PERSON> Luanne </PERSON> <PERSON> McGrain </PERSON>, a publicist for the zoo, said Friday. `` We've had a lot of doctors calling _ ` This is Dr. <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON>. May I speak to Mr. G. <PERSON> Raffe </PERSON>?''' For the second year running, the zoo turned the annual prank into a brief fund-raiser. Other zoos around the nation use the same tactics with people are fooled into calling on April Fools' Day. The switchboard answered calls Friday with `` NYZS,'' the call letters of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zoological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. When callers said they were returning a call from Mr. <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON>, they were transferred to a volunteer phone bank. `` They say, ` Mr. <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> is being fed right now. You have reached the Bronx Zoo. Somebody's played a joke on you for April Fools' Day But while I have you on the phone, would you care to make a donation?''' <PERSON> McGrain </PERSON> said. `` If they can stop laughing long enough, generally people do make a pledge.'' Callers wound up making $ 4,000 in donations, which <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> has promised to match.
