<HEAD>Dead Locusts Littering Beaches Near Rome</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of dead African desert locusts have shown up on beaches just outside <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> reported Saturday, prompting concerns some swarms might reach <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> alive. <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> officials said winds must have pushed the insects from <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> toward <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and that they died in the cold weather. The Italian press expressed concern that warmer weather might allow future swarms of locusts to survive and thrive. The <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> daily Il Tempo described the scene on the beach as `` the sign of a narrowly missed invasion, or worse, of an invasion that lies at the gates.'' But experts have said <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> will not be hit by the same invasion of locusts that has spread over <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tunisia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>. Last month, the Rome-based <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> described the insect invasion in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> as the worst in 30 years.
