s week if the administration was considering seizing <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, said, `` No.'' But the spokesman told reporters accompanying <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> on <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> One on Friday that the administration was still `` reviewing options'' aimed at securing <PERSON> Noriegan </PERSON>'s departure. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> decision to send additional manpower, many of them military police officers, came in the wake of a march by Panamanian troops on a <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> hotel earlier in the week. During that incident, several <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> journalists were detained briefly, and authorities confiscated videotapes of four <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> television networks. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> would be kept abreast of several matters while the president and his wife, <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON>, relax at <ORGANIZATION> Rancho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> del </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cielo </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ynez </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION>. `` He'll get daily intelligence updates on world situations,'' the spokesman said. `` He could get special information on three or four areas of interest. One is <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, a continuing problem to keep an eye on.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> also will be kept informed of any progress that <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> makes as he renews the administration's <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> peacemaking efforts with visits to several countries in the region. The president also will be briefed on the goings-on in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, where the Marxist Sandinista regime is scheduled to enter talks with the Contra rebels Tuesday aimed at bringing about democratic reforms envisioned in a truce agreement signed March 23. But the political and governmental crisis in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> seemed sure to take much of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s attention. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has sought to minimize the possibility of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military force being used to oust <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. Last Monday, for instance, he told high school students in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, he did not think the citizens of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> wanted to see `` the great colossus of the North'' flex its muscles there. But the administration apparently has become increasingly frustrated as <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> has survived an array of economic sanctions. These include the withholding of payments the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> makes to the <ORGANIZATION> Panama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> under terms of the 1979 treaties providing for the canal to be gradually turned over to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> by the turn of the century. In another effort to turn the financial screws on <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, the administration on Thursday announced steps to stop <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollars from flowing into the Central American nation. The administration is concerned that the continuing flow of tax payments by <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> corporations with operations in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> has served to sustain the existing government headed by <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. The first family plans a quiet Easter vacation, which lasts through April 10. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said there were no plans for get-togethers at the ranch by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> relatives, and it could not be learned whether the first couple would leave the mountain to attend Easter services here _ as they did last year. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s lone public outing is an appearance Monday at a luncheon of some 75 supporters of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> presidential library. He is scheduled to make a foreign policy address to a convention of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nev. </LOCATION>, en route back to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on April 10.
