<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Mormon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> leaders today urged followers to love God above worldly success and prepare themselves for the second coming of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON>. In the opening session of the 158th Annual General Conference of The Church of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON> of Latter-day <ORGANIZATION> Saints </ORGANIZATION>, leaders said service to God and love of Christ should be the highest priority of the faithful. `` We should put God ahead of everyone else in our lives,'' said President <PERSON> Ezra </PERSON> <PERSON> Taft </PERSON> <PERSON> Benson </PERSON>, the 88-year-old spiritual leader of the 6.5 million member church. `` When we put God first, all other things fall into their proper places or drop out of our lives. Our love of God will govern the claims for our affection, the demands on our time, the interests we pursue and the order of our priorities,'' <PERSON> Benson </PERSON> said in prepared remarks. The sermon was the first of three scheduled to be delivered by <PERSON> Benson </PERSON>, who has been convalescing from a heart attack the past six months. Church spokesman <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Cahill </PERSON> said <PERSON> Benson </PERSON>, who served as secretary of agriculture during the <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> administration, appeared to be in good health and excellent spirits. <PERSON> Benson </PERSON> was one of 22 of the church's general authorities scheduled to speak during the conference's five sessions. General authorities are full-time clergy who lead the church under the direction of the First Presidency, which consists of <PERSON> Benson </PERSON> and counselors <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hinckley </PERSON> and <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Monson </PERSON>. Thousands of lay clergymen and other church members from around the world have gathered for the two-day conference held in the Tabernacle on Temple Square in downtown <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. During this morning's opening session, leaders stressed fundamental church doctrines, such as belief in resurrection and atonement of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> and the importance of missionary work. Leaders were expected to announce this afternoon that convert baptisms reached an all-time high during 1987. <PERSON> Cahill </PERSON> said the exact figure would not be released prior to the afternoon session, but said it was about 250,000. He said the church's full-time, volunteer missionary force also has reached an all-time high of 34,200 men and women. <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON>, of the Council of the Twelve Apostles, urged church members to prepare for <PERSON> Christ </PERSON>'s second coming, but said they should not believe the rapture necessarily is near at hand. The Council of the Twelve are second to the First Presidency in the church hierarchy, and assist in directing the church. `` Over the sweep of Christian history, by focusing on a few prophecies while neglecting others, some believers have prematurely expected the second coming. Today, while obviously closer to that great moment, we are in the same danger,'' <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON> said. `` On the other hand, smugness is also a real danger.'' <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON> noted that a number of Biblical prophecies said to be precursors of <PERSON> Christ </PERSON>'s return already have occurred. Among them, he said, is the return of the Jewish people to the Holy Land. <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Perry </PERSON>, of the Council of the Twelve, said Mormons should get involved in community affairs and promote honest government, neighborhood beautification and high educational standards. `` Rather than spend time complaining about the direction in which these institutions are going, we need to exert