up 5th graf, `No new...</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With 23 more deaths reported Saturday, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s troubled state of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> has suffered the bloodiest week since Sikh rebels first began calling for a separate nation six years ago. Last week's death toll of 120 has prompted calls for imposing a federal emergency in the northern state and already may have crippled the government's latest effort to reach a compromise with militants of the religious minority. Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> called the appointed governor of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state, <ORGANIZATION> S.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ray </ORGANIZATION>, and state Police Chief <PERSON> Julius </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ribiero </PERSON> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> on Saturday to plan new initiatives against the violence. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> told reporters that the government would keep up its `` relentless war'' against the Sikh radicals who have been blamed for more than 630 killings this year. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> said Sikh militants shot to death six people Saturday night in the village of <LOCATION> Ragarh </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> district, adding to the 17 deaths reported since Friday night. No new government actions were announced Saturday, but Sikhs in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> expressed fears that <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s goverment would declare an emergency, severely limiting civil rights and imposing harsh police rule. `` This is an excuse by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> to impose emergency on the state,'' <PERSON> Darshan </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> <PERSON> Ragi </PERSON>, a Sikh religious leader, said Saturday at his home near <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>'s capital, <LOCATION> Chandigarh </LOCATION>. `` The bullet is not an answer to any problem, either from the militants or <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>.'' At the same time, opposition political leaders and some in <LOCATION> Gandhi </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> demanded action. And three radical groups issued a statement blaming the latest killings on police agents. `` All this is being done to defame the militant Sikh youths in the eyes of the Sikh masses so that the movement for <LOCATION> Khalistan </LOCATION> is weakened,'' said a statement from the radical groups. L.K. <PERSON> Advani </PERSON>, leader of the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peoples </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, demanded in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> that <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> impose a security belt along <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>'s border with <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, believed to be the source of the AK-47 assault rifles used by the rebels in their latest onslaught. Past efforts to seal the porous border, the traditional domain of smugglers on both sides, have failed. Harsh police action, exemplified by the Indian army's raid on the Sikhs' Golden Temple in <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> in 1984, has succeeded only in turning ordinary Sikhs against the government. The June 1984 raid to drive radicals from the shrine left more than 1,200 people dead, most of them Sikhs. Soon afterwards, Sikh bodyguards killed Prime Minister <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>, who was <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s mother Sikh radicals began openly demanding an independent <LOCATION> Khalistan </LOCATION> _ `` land of the pure'' in the Punjabi language. The killings are spiraling despite the <LOCATION> Gandhi </LOCATION> government's direct federal rule over <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> since last May when it invoked Indian law to dislodge the elected state government of Sikh moderates In March alone, 272 victims were gunned down, compared to 215 who died in the first three months of last year. The latest police reports confirm the pattern of random killings with the victims both Hindus and Sikhs. In the neighboring villages of <LOCATION> Tara </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Kaler </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Gurdaspur </LOCATION> district, two sets of Hindu brothers, in their 60s and 70s, were shot to death Friday night by four men with AK-47 rifles. In <LOCATION> Tara </LOCATION>, about 30 miles south of <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>, all but two of the 50 houses in the village were deserted by families fleeing the persistent violence. <PERSON> Ram </PERSON> <PERSON> Lal </PERSON>, a Hindu, said he and a few other villagers had been coming during the day to mind their fields and shops. After Friday night's slayings, he said: `` We will not come back at all. We are not able to stay here with the terror.'' Sikhs, whose religion is a mixture of <LOCATION> Hinduism </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Islam </ORGANIZATION>, make up only 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 800 million population, but they are a majority in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. The radicals argue that only a separate Sikh nation can save the minority faith from being overwhelmed by the Hindus, who comprise more than 80 percent of the country's people. Ironically, some Sikh sources say the upsurge in killings results from a new effort by the government to find a compromise with the militants through <PERSON> Jasbir </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> <PERSON> Rode </PERSON>, a 34-year-old Sikh preacher. Rode was among about 40 Sikhs who were freed in early March after being imprisoned without trial. He was promptly elected to the most powerful post in the Sikh faith amid reports his freedom was part of a government move to compromise with the radicals _ or divide them. Rode has denied there were any conditions to his release, and the government has not publicly outlined its