<HEAD>Reagan Fears U.S.Decline in Scientific Resarch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> voiced fear Saturday that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> could slip to a second-rate world power in technology, saying scientific research is `` an indispensable investment in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s future.'' `` We can travel as far as the eye of our imagination can see,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said in his weekly radio address to the nation. `` But one thing is certain: If we do n't, others will, and we'll fall behind.'' `` This is why I've urged <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to devote more money to research,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said in the speech delivered from his ranch in the <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ynez </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> near this seaside resort city. `` This year, we'll begin work on the great-grandchild of those particle accelerators that have meant so much to our economic growth,'' he said. `` It's called the super-conducting supercollider. And it will harness the galloping technology of superconductivity so we can explore sub-atomic particles in ways we've never been able to before.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> also said that `` we'll also continue developing the space station. When it's in orbit, the space station will let us perform once-impossible experiments in the weightless environment of outer space, and understand our world and universe better.'' `` Meanwhile, back on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>, we will be pursuing breakthroughs in biotechnology that promise to revolutionize medicine, agriculture and protection of the environment,'' he said. But in his talk, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> acknowledged that scientific research is expensive. `` Some say that we ca n't afford it _ that we're strapped for cash,'' he said. `` Well, leadership means making hard choices, even in an election year.'' Without citing dollars-and-cents figures, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said that federal spending for scientific research is 58 percent higher than a decade ago, after discounting for inflation. But he indicated this is still not enough. `` We've put our research budget under a microscope and looked for quality and cost-effectiveness,'' he said. `` We've put together the best program for the taxpayers' dollars. `` After all, the American tradition of hope is one we ca n't afford to forget `` The problem here is that science, unlike a bridge or an interstate highway or a courthouse, has no local constituency,'' he said. `` Federal funding for science is in jeopardy because of budget constraints. That's why it's my duty as president to draw its importance to your attention and that of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>.''
