<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Rembrandt     04-02 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Rembrandt,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Restoration Shows How Master Reworked Painting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Restoration work on <PERSON> Rembrandt </PERSON>'s `` Danae,'' which was cut and splashed with acid by an attacker in 1985, has revealed how the Dutch painter reworked the 17th century masterpiece, the <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency said Saturday. Restoration experts in <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> using X-rays, ultraviolet and infrared light, have completed the first stage of their work and now are getting ready to retouch the areas where the original paint was destroyed, the report said. A `` case history'' of hundreds of pages has been recorded, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. The painting was damaged June 15, 1985, by what officials described as a `` madman'' who threw sulphuric acid on it and slashed it twice with a knife at <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION>'s Hermitage museum. Soviet art officials have said the damage was serious, but never have said specifically how much of the painting was destroyed. Restorers, including chemists, biologists, physicists and other scientists, began work immediately on the canvas. The painting depicts the mother of <PERSON> Perseus </PERSON>, who, according to Greek legend, killed <PERSON> Medusa </PERSON> and her head of snakes. Soviet art books say <PERSON> Rembrandt </PERSON> painted `` Danae'' in 1636 and repainted it in 1646-1647. `` X-ray studies showed that <PERSON> Rembrandt </PERSON> had repainted the gesture of the right hand, changed the appearance of the old woman looking from behind the canopy, that he had painted over <PERSON> Danae </PERSON>'s earrings and beads, and that he had altered her facial features several times in the course of the work,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. Experts also established that the 81-inch canvas was actually two pieces that had been skillfully sewn together, covered first with a brown primer, a layer of gray and then whiting. `` It is our immutable principle not to paint over even a single millimeter of the author's painting,'' <PERSON> Yevgeny </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON>, head of the restoration effort, told <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>. `` Now we are beginning work on those sections where the layer of paint had been washed off, and advancing from the sides of the painting to the four epicenters that suffered most from the acid. We are drawing copies of ` <PERSON> Danae </PERSON>' to master <PERSON> Rembrandt </PERSON>'s style,'' he said. The experts also tried to restore the painting's lacquer, which had seriously deteriorated in several places, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. The report said experts would not speculate on when restoration work would be done, but that they were confident the painting would be displayed once more in the Hermitage when the work is completed.
