<HEAD>McGovern Warns Against Brokered Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former Democratic presidential candidate <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON> on Saturday warned Democrats that an attempt to deny the party's nomination to the front-runner at the convention could spell defeat in November. `` I do n't want to see a big, divisive fight at the convention and a desperate attempt to block the front-runner because I think that would bring a repeat of 1972,'' <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON> said efforts by some Democrats to block his nomination despite his delegate lead going into the 1972 Democratic convention split the party and contributed to his landslide defeat to then-President <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> in the general election. `` It really cost us heavily. The fallout was devastating,'' <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON> said. `` Those last-minute, desperation blocking efforts contributed to the Democratic defeat in the fall,'' he said. `` We should not repeat that experience in 1988.'' <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON>'s advice to fall in line behind a front-runner echoes a similar call by <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON>, who also wants the nomination settled before the convention. <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON> said a brokered convention is unnecessary because `` the voters are the brokers and they are making it clear that <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> are the two candidates who command the most support.'' `` After the last primary, we should rally around whichever of these two front-runners has the most delegates,'' he said. If <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> end up in a `` virtual dead heat'' after all the primaries, then the convention delegates should decide which will be the candidiate, <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON> said. `` But if one of the candidates compiles a significant first-place win, he is entitled to the nomination,'' <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON> said. <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON> said the Democratic race has narrowed to `` a two-man race now'' between <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. He said neither Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> nor Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> is likely to pull ahead, but he said he was not suggesting they drop out. `` That's a judgment they should make, but I think that if at the end they come up as short as they are now, they should get behind the front-runner,'' he said. <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON> has not endorsed anyone in the race yet. He said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> `` offers a message of hope and reconciliation'' and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> `` offers a record of experience and competence in government.'' Democrats should evaluate both `` progressive spirited men'' and nominate the one with the most delegates, he said.
