<HEAD>French Ferry Strikers Vote to Man Ships</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALAIS, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Striking ferry sailors voted Saturday to return to work, ending their 17-day walkout in time to carry Easter holiday travelers across the English Channel. Seamen in the French ports of <LOCATION> Calais </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dunkirk </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Dieppe </LOCATION> voted to accept an agreement worked out Friday between their unions and the maritime arm of the state-run railroad. The accord provides for employment guarantees, better working conditions and higher salaries for part-time employees. The workers were readying three idled ferries to serve Easter Sunday passengers. They join two British ferries that had been carrying the backed-up traffic alone. But on the British side of the Channel, talks broke down Friday between ferry workers and P and O European Ferries and a two-month strike continued.
