the grand jury without bringing charges, he could retain his appointment or seek reappointment if new evidence surfaces later, the source said. The grand jury is expected to question <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>, his wife, <PERSON> Ursula </PERSON>, and <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Circuit Judge <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ginsburg </PERSON>, who was head of the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s antitrust division during the breakup of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. In regard to the pipeline, <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>, who was <PERSON> Rappaport </PERSON>'s lawyer, obtained <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s help in arranging a meeting with then-National Security Adviser <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> McFarlane </PERSON> to help boost the pipeline project. Four months later, <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> wrote <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> a memo that <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> said was based on conversations with <PERSON> Rappaport </PERSON>. It said a portion of up to $ 700 million from the oil pipeline would be funneled to the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> of then-Israeli Prime Minister <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON>. That raised questions of whether <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>, who has said he does n't recall reading that portion of the memo, may have violated the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act barring bribes to foreign officials Without being able to question <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> or <PERSON> Rappaport </PERSON>, <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> is at a dead end. Another part of <PERSON> McKay </PERSON>'s probe the independent counsel says he has insufficient evidence on which to seek indictment is <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s ownership of $ 14,000 i