<HEAD>Byrd Wants Heat On Reagan to Sign Trade Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> asked Americans on Saturday to pressure President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> into signing comprehensive trade legislation. `` Write the president and tell him ... that this trade bill will help you and help <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> feel proud again,'' <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, urged in the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s weekly radio Under a compromise worked out by <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> negotiators Thursday night, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade representative would have the authority to impose import curbs on the goods of nations who violate trade agreements. The president could waive the curbs if he thought their cost would outweigh the benefit. Presidential spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> on Friday renewed the threat of a veto by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, saying the bill unreasonably ties the president's hands and that the administration has `` grave reservations'' about it. <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> complained that `` the president has done nothing but cry protectionism and wave his veto pen'' as the ability of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to compete has eroded. `` This is not the time for a veto,'' he said. `` The trade bill is a strong comprehensive bill that helps American workers help themselves.'' He said the Democrats' `` goal has been a bill that the president will sign,'' adding, `` We have extended our hand in cooperation.'' `` The president may not understand what this bill means to the American worker ... I think you do,'' <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said in urging his listeners to write to the White House. The measure also would impose import restrictions to punish <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> for a subsidiary's role in selling computerized submarine propeller milling equipment to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. And, it would require employers to give workers a 60-day notice of plant closings and large layoffs.
