<FIRST>r w AM-Democrats-RadioText     04-02 0770</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Democrats-Radio Text,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Trade-Democrats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is the text of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s weekly radio address, delivered Saturday by <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>: Good afternoon This is Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> from <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is putting the finishing touches on a very important trade bill. It is not a minute too soon. Our nation's trade policy is in shambles. You know it. I know it. We import more than we export. We send more of our money overseas than we get back. We are losing American jobs. We are losing our industrial base. We are in hock to foreign lenders. Once it was n't so. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> traded hard all over the world. The result was money in the bank and jobs for American workers. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> ran a trade surplus. `` Made in the <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION>'' was on the product that everybody looked for. Americans took pride in being No. 1. Now our ability to compete is eroding. For seven years the president has refused to act. `` Free trade,'' he says. What about fair trade? The president has done nothing but cry protectionism and wave his veto pen. Yet, unless we change the way <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> trades the tide of change will sweep our economic destiny out of our hands. You know what I am talking about. You see it in the frustration of all the young families who can not afford to buy their first home. You understand it when American companies take their jobs overseas. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is rapidly developing a treadmill economy; everyone is working harder just to keep up; yet we still seem to be losing ground to our foreign competition. Our prosperity has always been built on working smarter as well as harder. Yet, despite our new technology and effort to compete, we have been losing the productivity race. For years the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has left trade policy to the whims of the international marketplace and our foreign competition. The administration has refused to act. It has had a do-nothing trade policy. It is time to get <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> moving again. The stakes are high and measured in jobs, and in the life style we pass on to our children, and in our vital national security. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will soon send the president a comprehensive trade bill. We are not ready to say good-bye to the <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> of our dreams. What must be done to rebuild <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s dreams? First, <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> must boost its exports. Selling more goods overseas lowers the deficit. It is that simple. Our bill gives the president new tools to open new markets for American products. Second, we must take steps to promote <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s long run competitive strengths. We want to see more investment in individuals and in ideas. That means a better educated work force, stronger laws to protect American inventions from piracy by foreign firms. Third, we want to give <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> industry and workers the opportunity to retool and retrain quickly. I have seen the devastating impact in my own state of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> where closed factories leave workers and whole communities struggling for their economic future. This trade bill sharply improves the opportunities for workers to retrain, to start new careers. If American workers want to move to expanding parts of the job market they ought to have that chance. Finally, this trade bill would prevent foreign investors from dominating industries vital to our national security. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> can not control its destiny if our foreign competition is buying up our assets. Opening new markets for exports, giving <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> industry a leg up to retool, creating new opportunities for American workers to retrain, keeping <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s destiny in <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> hands, educating our children for a prosperous future _ these are the essentials of this trade bill, which the president would veto. In the last few months you have heard a lot of talk about this trade bill from the president. I am sure you will hear more. Our goal has been a bill that the president will sign. We have extended our hand in cooperation. This is not a time for a veto. The trade bill is a strong comprehensive bill that helps American industry and helps American workers help themselves. The president may not understand what this bill means to the American worker, to young families who can not buy their first home, to the unemployed worker who has lost his job to a foreign competitor. I think you do. So write the president. Tell him of your concerns. Let him know that this trade bill will help <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> feel proud again. Let's put <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s future back in <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> hands.
</TEXT>
