<HEAD>Iraqi Pilot Says He Is Shocked By Chemical Weapon Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An Iraqi pilot held captive by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> said Saturday he was shocked to learn how many civilians were killed in an Iraqi gas attack on a border town and assumed the raid was a mistake. Air Force Maj. <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakr </PERSON> <PERSON> Salaleh </PERSON>, 31, said he was shown an Iranian documentary of the aftermath of the raid two weeks ago on the Kurdish town of <LOCATION> Halabja </LOCATION>, in northeastern <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. `` All of us suffer seeing these pictures,'' <PERSON> Salaleh </PERSON> told reporters in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>. `` I ask God to take all of them to paradise.'' <PERSON> Salaleh </PERSON> said he was aware that the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> air force had been dropping chemical weapons but added: `` We are under orders. We are officers.'' He said the chemical bombs were dropped to halt Iranian advances into <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> territory. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> have been at war since September 1980. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has denied using chemical weapons, which are banned by international law. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has said it captured large tracts of territory in northeast <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> in league with Kurdish separatists. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> said Saturday it routed the attackers. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> says chemical weapons raids on <LOCATION> Halabja </LOCATION>, 160 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>, killed 5,000 people and wounded another 5,000 on March 16-17. The Iraqi pilot said his Soviet-built Sukhoi Su-22 was shot down 30 miles south of <LOCATION> Halabja </LOCATION> on March 18 after the gas attacks were over. He said he earlier had released four conventional-explosive 1,100-pound bombs over uninhabited territory when clouds prevented bombing of a road. <PERSON> Salaleh </PERSON> said he ejected and parachuted into Iranian-held territory. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has claimed shooting down more than a dozen <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> warplanes since mid-March. The Iraqi officer said he was not involved in the <LOCATION> Halabja </LOCATION> attack. He said he was assigned to drop a chemical bomb into wetland border territory of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> in 1983 to prevent an Iranian offensive there. The bomb he dropped then was put on his plane by a crew in civilian clothes who arrived at the air force base with a truck and trailer with civilian plates, <PERSON> Salaleh </PERSON> said. He estimated about 50 planes raided <LOCATION> Halabja </LOCATION> from March 16-18 after the Iranians and Kurdish guerrillas captured the town. <PERSON> Salaleh </PERSON>, speaking in relatively good English, said he thought the chemical-bomb attack was a `` mistake.'' He said one possible explanation was that <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> intelligence did not know the inhabitants were still in the town. <PERSON> Salaleh </PERSON> said he had been well treated since he was captured but had not yet been transferred to a prisoner-of-war camp. He said he had heard on Iraqi television that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has used artillery gas shells but had no confirmation of this, adding that <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> forces had been issued gas masks. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has denied using the internationally banned chemical weapons, but has said it has the capability to produce them. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has repeatedly denied using the weapons, while coupling its denials with assurances it will use `` all means'' at its disposal to defend its territory.
