<SECOND>AM-Federated Sale, Bjt,0738</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sale of Department Store Giant Will Bring Changes to Retail
Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The sale of <ORGANIZATION> Federated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> to <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is more than just a retailer changing hands. Analysts fear the $ 6.58 billion deal may lead to more centralization and less innovation in the retail industry. When ownership of the nation's fifth-largest retailer passes to <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION>, the Toronto-based developer will do what it did when it acquired <ORGANIZATION> Allied </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> at the end of 1986: pare the company down, sell its less attractive divisions and keep its most profitable stores. The forecasts are that <PERSON> Federated </PERSON>, now a collection of diverse department and specialty stores, will become a centralized retailer with few differences among its various units. `` The structure will be much more of a chain store company,'' said <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Loeb </PERSON>, a retail industry analyst with the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Morosky </PERSON>, the president of <ORGANIZATION> Allied </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION>, denied Saturday that <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> would centralize buying operations of <PERSON> Federated </PERSON> department store divisions that include <ORGANIZATION> Bloomingdale </ORGANIZATION>'s and <ORGANIZATION> Abraham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Straus </PERSON> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Lazarus </PERSON> in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Burdine </PERSON>'s in Operations such as distribution will be centralized, he said, but the stores' merchandise mix `` will be determined by the local department store divisions.'' However, <PERSON> Loeb </PERSON> predicted that under <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Federated </PERSON> would consolidate operations such as purchasing and marketing that are now carried out separately by the <PERSON> Federated </PERSON> units. `` The merchandise will be uniform,'' said <PERSON> Loeb </PERSON>, who has been tracking the industry for almost 40 years. `` It's bad for the whole industry.'' Retail industry watchers want to see what <PERSON> Loeb </PERSON> called `` innovativeness and testing,'' which helps develop new styles and trends. When there are more retailers buying and experimenting, there is a greater opportunity for growth in the retail industry. Friday's announcement of an agreement between <PERSON> Federated </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> ended a grueling takeover battle that began Jan. 25. <PERSON> Federated </PERSON> resisted <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION>'s overtures for a month, agreed to negotiate with the Canadian company, and then in early March accepted a buyout offer from <ORGANIZATION> R.H. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Macy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Inc The wrangling continued for yet another month, until <PERSON> Macy </PERSON> agreed on Friday to bow out. But the New York-based retailer came away from the fight with the <PERSON> Federated </PERSON> divisions it wanted most, <PERSON> Bullock </PERSON>'s stores in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> and the San Francisco-based <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Magnin </PERSON> chain. Many retail industry analysts were rooting for <ORGANIZATION> Macy </ORGANIZATION> to win the battle outright. They believed <PERSON> Macy </PERSON> would have re-energized <PERSON> Federated </PERSON>'s department store divisions in much the way <ORGANIZATION> Macy </ORGANIZATION> has revitalized its own image in recent years. <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION>, they believed, was interested more in <PERSON> Federated </PERSON>'s real estate than its retail operations. The stores would give <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Campeau </PERSON> an instant entree into major shopping malls in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The expected sale of several of <PERSON> Federated </PERSON>'s divisions represents a chance for the retailing industry to move in a new direction, but whether that happens depends on who buys the stores. <PERSON> Morosky </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> will retain <ORGANIZATION> Bloomingdale </ORGANIZATION>'s, <ORGANIZATION> Abraham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Straus </PERSON>, <PERSON> Lazarus </PERSON> and <PERSON> Burdine </PERSON>'s, as well as Tennessee-based <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON>'s and Atlanta-based <PERSON> Rich </PERSON>'s department stores. <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> has already agreed to sell <PERSON> Federated </PERSON>'s Texas-based <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>'s and Boston-based <ORGANIZATION> Filene </ORGANIZATION>'s department stores to <ORGANIZATION> May </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Federated </PERSON>'s discount and specialty store chains and its supermarkets divisions are expected to go on the block However, <PERSON> Morosky </PERSON> said, `` After we comple te our review, we might choose to keep certain divisions.'' <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> wants to sell some of the divisions to pay off debt incurred in the <PERSON> Federated </PERSON> purchase and to simplify operations, <PERSON> Morosky </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Tashjian </PERSON>, an analyst with the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Seidler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Amdec </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said recently that if <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> sells <PERSON> Federated </PERSON>'s units to larger companies _ such as May _ it would continue the trend toward central control and `` sameness.'' However, he said, if the stores are sold to smaller companies or to entrepreneurial management groups, it would mean increased competition, which in turn leads to growth in the retail industry. `` The long-term benefit is to the consumer,'' <PERSON> Tashjian </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Morosky </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> already has received inquiries from retailers, existing management and real estate developers about some of the Federated stores. He said the stores would go on sale several days after the purchase of <PERSON> Federated </PERSON> is completed.
