<HEAD>Patent Backlog Stymies Biotech Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s biotechnology industry, hailed Saturday by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> for its `` promise to revolutionize medicine, agriculture and protection of the environment,'' is seriously hampered by government delays on patent applications, congressional and industry officials say. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, in a radio address from his <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> ranch, called for renewed <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> determination to remain the world's scientific leader, noting that `` over the years, we've secured far more patents than any other country.'' He cited biotechnology as one of the most fertile fields for exploration. For hundreds of small biotech companies developing new drugs, plants and other products through molecular biology, the issuance of a patent can mean instant success. But the wait can take more than four years, leaving some firms to ponder the risk of marketing their products without patent protection. In some of the biotech examining units at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patents </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trademarks </ORGANIZATION>, `` it takes an average of 27 months just to open an application file, and another 25 months to award or deny a patent,'' complained Rep. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ore </LOCATION>, whose <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Small </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee is looking into the problem. Biotech products have begun to pour out of the laboratories of the 12-year-old industry, doubling the backlog of patent applications from 3,903 in 1985 to 7,821 by August of last year. By some estimates, 11,000 applications are now pending. According to industry forecasts, biotech sales in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> markets will total $ 650 million this year. Barring further bureaucratic snags, the industry projects domestic sales of $ 3.4 billion by 1993 and $ 13.2 billion by 1998. International sales could triple the domestic figure, officials say But `` the longer it takes of patents to be issued, the longer we work in a black hole,'' says <PERSON> Hubert </PERSON> <PERSON> J.P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schoemaker </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Centocor </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. That complaint is echoed by officials of <ORGANIZATION> Genentech </ORGANIZATION>, which has begun marketing a much-acclaimed drug known as TPA _ a clot buster for heart attack victims <ORGANIZATION> Genentech </ORGANIZATION>'s patent application is still pending, however, and several other companies are planning to market their own TPA drugs. Turnover among biotech patent examiners, lured to private companies by higher pay, has been part of the problem. <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON> said the turnover was 50 percent last year, though the patent office has created 10 new biotech positions for a total of 42, and recently consolidated all those positions within a special biotech unit. Patent Commissioner <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Quigg </PERSON> said, meanwhile, that the office is seeking approval from the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Personnel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> to create special pay rates for the examiners, who usually have a doctorate or master's degree in molecular biology or biochemistry. <PERSON> Quigg </PERSON> said the goal of the patent office is to process all applications within 18 months, but that target likely wo n't be met until 1993 or 1994. To encourage inventions, the Constitution gives inventors the right to a short-term exclusive monopoly on products that result from their new ideas. Currently, the monopoly lasts 17 years. To make sure the invention is indeed new, and not an obvious twist to existing technology, the patent office examines applications in light of previous patents. Lack of patents leads firms to hold their products off the market, or to risk theft of their invention if they sell without full protection. Since the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> does not publish applications after 18 months, as all other major countries do, the backlog may lead several companies to undertake duplicate research they would not perform if they knew someone else was likely to win a patent. `` Increasing backlogs in the processing of patent applications will have serious deleterious effects on continuing investment and the maintenance of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' leadership position,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rathmann </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Amgen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Thousand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oaks </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, in testimony to <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON>'s subcommittee. <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, a vice president of <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a Wall Street investment firm, found in a survey of four dozen prospectuses by biotechnology companies that nearly all mentioned uncertainty about patent protection as a potential risk for investors. She gave the subcommittee charts of price movements of several stocks, up when specific patents were awarded and down when patent disputes broke out between two companies. The applications backlog appears to be growing at 20 percent a year, she reported. `` With the lack of clarity of property rights in biotechnology in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, many companies are developing similar products _ expending valuable resources, both human and financial _ on me-too programs,'' she said.
