<HEAD>Indian Troops Seek Elusive Sri Lankan Rebels</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with three grafs to CORRECT spelling of sarong. Pick up
4th pvs, `Every few...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATTICALOA, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Eight months after they landed to enforce a peace accord between rival ethnic groups, Indian soldiers are chasing a faceless enemy. The Tamil rebels, who have waged a four-year war of guerrilla fighting and terrorism against <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s Sinhalese majority, seem to be everywhere and nowhere at once. Every young man is a potential foe, whether dressed in trousers or the plaid sarongs favored in the steamy heat of this tropical island 18 miles off <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s southern coast. Every few miles along potholed roads, <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> soldiers man sandbagged checkpoints where they halt travelers who come on foot, on bicycles and jammed into minibuses. Despite an Indian force estimated at 50,000 by the Indians and as high as 100,000 by Sri Lankan officials, a ragtag band of <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tiger </ORGANIZATION> rebels continues to kill and maim Indian soldiers, massacre Sinhalese villagers and extort money from Tamils, Sinhalese and Moslems alike. The Indians say there are about 2,500 hard-core fighters in the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eelam </ORGANIZATION>, the largest rebel group. The <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> claim there are only 175. More than 8,000 Sri Lankans, mostly Sinhalese, have been killed since 1984. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has lost at least 400 soldiers since Oct. 10, 1987, when it launched an offensive to disarm the <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION>. The Indians sent troops to control the rebels as part of a peace plan they sponsored in July 1987. The agreement granted some autonomy to Tamils, but it was rejected by extremists on both sides of the conflict. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s northern neighbor, has a large Tamil minority of its own. Despite <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s firepower, armor, lumbering troop trucks, darting Jeep patrols and helicopters _ and allied government forces _ the <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> slip from village to village and even into big towns like <LOCATION> Batticaloa </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Arapattai </LOCATION>, 5 miles south of <LOCATION> Batticaloa </LOCATION> on <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s eastern coast, Indian soldiers recently checked pedestrians' identity cards and munched snacks purchased in local shops. A five-minute walk away, a man sought by the Indians for harboring Tiger fighters said the rebels could not be vanquished. `` Our fight is reasonable. We must win,'' he said, switching on an electric fan as an elderly relative tended his infant twins. The man asked not to be identified, although the <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION> know his name and where he lives. They also know that the minute they come after him, his neighbors will sound an alarm and he will slip away _ as he has done several times before _ through the fences of woven palm fronds that make <PERSON> Arapattai </PERSON> look like an impenetrable maze. The <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> are fighting for an autonomous region in northern and eastern <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>. Although Tamils make up only 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people, they are a majority in Northern and Eastern provinces. In Eastern Province's <LOCATION> Batticaloa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION>, the population of about 365,000 is 72 percent Tamil. Sinhalese account for only 3 percent there, while Moslems comprise 25 percent. The Tamils say they have been discriminated against in education, jobs and by a 1956 law that made Sinhalese the official language of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>. Tamils are mainly Hindu, and the Sinhalese are Buddhists. <LOCATION> Batticaloa </LOCATION>, population 46,000, is a town of poor fishermen, small shops and many churches, monuments to the missionary efforts of the Dutch, <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION> and British colonial eras. The Indian presence keeps armed <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> out of clear sight. But, according to residents who feared for their safety if their names were published, the <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> make themselves felt in other ways. `` They send notes asking for money. People who refuse are killed,'' a middle-aged Tamil said. `` They have people in the banks, so they know how much money we have.'' But that Tamil, like others who described the <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION>' fund-raising tactics, defended the rebels' cause as a just fight for Tamil rights `` Just because they're militant, they're not unreasonable,'' said one Tamil bureaucrat. A occasional land mine or hand grenade explodes in <LOCATION> Batticaloa </LOCATION> near a group of the Indian soldiers or the predominantly Sinhalese Sri Lankan police force. Sometimes, the Indian response is disciplined. Other times, it verges on panic, <LOCATION> Batticaloa </LOCATION> residents said. On March 26, a grenade was thrown at the Sri Lankan police headquarters. No one was hurt by the grenade, but it prompted three hours of gunfire that injured a half-dozen people, including two schoolchildren. Sri Lankan police officers declined to say whether their men fired, but <LOCATION> Batticaloa </LOCATION> residents said the police apparently started the shooting and the Indians followed with automatic rifle fire. `` The roads were packed with children,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, a Jesuit from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> who has spent the past 40 years at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michael </ORGANIZATION>'s school. `` The schoolchildren just panicked. They dropped their books and bicycles and ran.'' An Indian major, speaking on condition of anonymity, admitted that mistakes have been made. `` There is no doubt there is some confusion,'' he said.
