<HEAD>Soviet Armenian Leader May Have Instigated Disturbances</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The disturbances in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> may have been instigated by a local leader who was a target of <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s anti-corruption campaign, according to analysts. The local leader may have capitalized on unrest exacerbated by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s drive for economic reform, known as `` perestroika,'' and his allowance of greater public debate of some topics, known as `` glasnost,'' according to a government analyst. Similar disturbances have been reported in each of the 15 republics in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. And in many instances, the demonstrations grew out of <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> resentment of <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> efforts to help non-Russians by giving them jobs and raising their living standards, scholar <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Goble </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said in an article last year. `` Many Russians came to the conclusion that what had appeared to be reasonable affirmative action for the non-Russians was in fact unreasonable reverse discrimination against themselves,'' <PERSON> Goble </PERSON> wrote. That system worked under the late Soviet leader <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>, who tolerated corruption and widespread inefficiency in the economy. Under his leadership, a Russian and a non-Russian were frequently allowed to hold redundant jobs. But <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, in his effort to streamline the economy, has stepped on a lot of ethnic toes. `` It is not that he is coming down hard on any ethnic group. It is that he is trying to make the economy more efficient,'' said <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lubin </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> professor. Ostensibly, the demonstrations in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, a largely Christian republic, stemmed from Armenian desire to administer the largely Armenian region of <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, which is in neighboring <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, a predominately Moslem republic. But the unrest began after party newspapers criticized the Armenian party leader, <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Demirchyan </PERSON>, said an administration source, who like other government analysts interviewed, spoke on condition of anonymity. <PERSON> Demirchyan </PERSON>, 55, named to his post in 1974, was attacked last June by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, who said that reforms were `` stuck in a rut'' in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, and that <PERSON> Demirchyan </PERSON> and his underlings showed `` totally unjustified complacency'' toward corruption. Reformers in the <ORGANIZATION> Armenia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> attempted to oust <PERSON> Demirchyan </PERSON> during a meeting of the party <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> last December, but were thwarted, according to <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON>, a Soviet-watcher based in <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION>. The authoritative <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> daily Pravda hinted strongly of a purge in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. `` The absolute majority of Armenian working people are honest persons who conscientiously attend their duty, and it is not their fault that the process of democratization and renewal is meeting with fierce resistance of perestroika,'' Pravda said in December. `` People yearn for genuine changes.'' The demonstrations in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> began two months later `` with either the complicity or encouragement of <PERSON> Demirchyan </PERSON>,'' said a government analyst. `` We believe he backed them, or encouraged them, to warn <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> that getting rid of him could cause trouble.'' <PERSON> Demirchyan </PERSON> has survived the upheaval, although some party leaders in <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> have been removed. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s efficiency drive has cost local jobs in <LOCATION> Kazakhstan </LOCATION>, the scene of riots in December 1986. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> abolished the <ORGANIZATION> Kazakhstan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Non-Ferrous </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metallurgy </ORGANIZATION>, transferring its functions to a parallel ministry in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, but `` throwing a lot of educated Kazakhs out of work,'' said a government analyst. Similarly, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s highly celebrated campaign against alcohol has cost jobs in the vineyards of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, creating tension there, said the analyst. The ethnic unrest has prompted <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to announce that he will convene the policy-making <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to discuss the issue at an as yet unannounced date. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> probably will continue to crack down, as he did in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and neighboring <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, `` to show people that they ca n't get what they want by going to the streets,'' an analyst said.
