/LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> called for a continuation of the Camp David peace process, which he said was the `` unfulfilled'' vision of the late Egyptian President <PERSON> Anwar </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON> and former Israeli Prime Minister <PERSON> Menachem </PERSON> <PERSON> Begin </PERSON>. `` Why? Because few <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> leaders have had the courage to see the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> as <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON> saw it. Few Arab leaders have had the wisdom to choose reconciliation over conflict, to choose hope instead of hate; to prepare for the future rather than relive the wars of the past,'' he said. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> made abundantly clear his commitment to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. `` The first thing anyone must understand about the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> is that we will never let <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> down,'' he said. `` For decades, <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> leaders have know and the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people have understood, that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s fate is our fate ... that our security interests are linked and that our historical and cultural bonds can not and will not broken. `` <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> _ like the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ is a special place.'' After support for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> laid down three other tenets of his <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> policy. The second was the necessity for direct negotiations between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and its neighbors. Third was a continuation of the Camp David understandings on the future of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> strip. `` That framework recognizes the right of the people of the territories to shape their own destiny in a way that is consistent with <LOCATION> Israel