<SECOND>AM-Lost Bridge,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Dakota Looks For Caretaker For `Lost Bridge'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB IMRIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANDAREE, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The 500-foot highway of steel over the <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> is more than just a bridge to this small village on the Fort Berthold Indian Reservation. This one possesses personality, they say, so much so they refer to it by name _ Lost Bridge. The 20-foot-wide, three-span truss bridge was erected in 1929 when it only connected two dusty cattle trails, said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON>, assistant bridge engineer for the state <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. `` They built a bridge that had no access to it,'' said <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Redford </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Mandaree </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Now that state Highway 22 crosses the bridge, the state wants to build a replacement, and <ORGANIZATION> Mandaree </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> hopes to preserve the old span as a focus for development People old enough to remember its origin are still baffled. `` I do n't even know why they built it,'' <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Lone </PERSON> <PERSON> Fight </PERSON> said. Nobody used Lost Bridge before Garrison Dam was built downstream in the 1950s and <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sakakawea </LOCATION> blocked many roads, <PERSON> Pamela </PERSON> <PERSON> Black </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawk </PERSON> recalled. Eventually, Highway 22 became a paved ribbon of asphalt and the bridge, part of the shortest western route around the lake, got far more use. The state wants to replace it with a modern bridge that's 16 feet wider and can carry heavier loads, <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> said So the state is searching for a buyer for the steel structure and is offering $ 50,000 to aid in moving it. If no one takes the bridge, it will be torn down. <ORGANIZATION> Mandaree </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> is exploring the possibility of essentially adopting the bridge. The group envisions using it for a fishing site, the focal point of a place for prairie-weary travelers to stop for rest or a picnic, said <PERSON> Redford </PERSON>. That would preserve Lost Bridge for its historic and sentimental importance, she said. The bridge sits 10 miles south of <LOCATION> Mandaree </LOCATION> in a picturesque valley of rolling river bluffs that are void of any man-made structures except for the highway itself and an occasional highway sign. Driving into the valley, the sun-drenched metal bridge glistens as it stands against a backdrop of prairie grass. Any group that agrees to preserve the bridge gets at least $ 50,000 _ the estimated expense for tearing it down _ from the state, <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> said. The deadline for assuming ownership of bridge is November, he said. <ORGANIZATION> Mandaree </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> hopes to make a decision within the next few weeks, <PERSON> Redford </PERSON> said. `` We are looking right now into the liabilities and what the federal guidelines call for in maintaining a -LRB- historic -RRB- bridge,'' said <PERSON> Redford </PERSON>. `` The history is what makes it unique,'' <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> said. `` The fact they call it a lost bridge.'' A new bridge just west of <LOCATION> Lost </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION> will cost an estimated $ 1 million, he said. The state hopes to begin construction in 1990. In the early 1970s, the state tried to give away a rainbow-arch bridge over the <LOCATION> Cannonball </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> but found no takers, <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> recalled. `` They took a lot of pictures, wrote up quite a documentary on it, and destroyed the bridge,'' he said.
