vide the 160,000-member military. The charismatic former colonel remains widely admired in the military even though he was dismissed after his Aug. 28 coup attempt left at least 53 people dead. His escape was widely reported Saturday in the Filipino media, which normally curtail operations on Easter weekend. Scores of callers to <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> radio stations questioned how <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON> could have escaped without the help of the guards. Military Chief of Staff Gen. <PERSON> Renato </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Villa </PERSON> told reporters Saturday he accepted responsibility for the escape but would let Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> decide whether he should be relieved. `` Somehow, in one way or another, I bear responsibility for ensuring that our detainees are secured and procedures are followed,'' he said. Last month, the congressional Commission on Appointments approved de Villa's nomination as chief of staff. The move came despite opposition from some congressmen who felt the former Constabulary commander should have retired instead. Critics said extending his tour of duty limited promotion of younger officers and smacked of practices under ousted President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>. The escape also raised doubts whether the congressional commission would approve the recent nomination of Adm. <PERSON> Carlito </PERSON> <PERSON> Cunanan </PERSON>, former chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>, as navy commander. <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said they already had misgivings about <PERSON> Cunanan </PERSON> because of the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>'s inept handling of rescue efforts in a December collision of a Filipino passenger ship and oil tanker that killed 3,000 people. The escape took place as the military was enjoying new prestige for Tuesday's arrest of seven leading communists, including <PERSON> Romulo </PERSON> <PERSON> Kintanar </PERSON>, commander of the rebel <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON> had said the arrests showed that the military had overcome past divisions and could now act effectively. But on Saturday, he called the escape `` disturbing news.'' <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Villa </PERSON> said the search for <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON>, moreover, would divert military resources from the fight against the rebels. One Filipino politician also worried about the international impact of <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON>'s escape. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Osmena </PERSON> said it was bound to tarnish the government's image abroad and raise more doubts about the stability of the Aquino administration.
