<HEAD>Rain Drenches Central Gulf Coast, Deep Snow On Western Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 A storm centered over <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> spread rain and thunderstorms up and down the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> on Saturday, causing floods and tornadoes in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and trailing heavy snow across the western <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>. Heavy rain accompanied showers and thunderstorms across southern <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> into southern <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> during the morning. Widespread street flooding was reported across the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> area and north of <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pontchartrain </LOCATION>. Rainfall amounts in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> area ranged up to 9 inches since Friday evening, with 8.17 inches at <LOCATION> Gretna </LOCATION> and 6.09 inches at <LOCATION> Gramercy </LOCATION>. In east-central <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, 5.65 inches fell at Bayou Sorrel. During the six hours up to 1 p.m. EST, 2.08 inches of rain fell at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>' Lakefront Airport. Strong thunderstorms developed during the afternoon across parts of eastern <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and northwestern <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. Showers were scattered from western <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> through southern <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and northern <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, with most rain amounts less than an inch. Snow and blowing snow made travel difficult in northwestern <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> and northeastern <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, and most roads in the western two counties of the <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Panhandle </LOCATION> were closed. Snow amounts included 13 inches at <LOCATION> Goodland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>; 22 at <LOCATION> Timpas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>; 20 at <LOCATION> Walsh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION