<HEAD>Poll: Dukakis Holds Small Lead Over Jackson In Wisconsin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> held a narrow lead over the Rev. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in the week leading up to Tuesday's <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> presidential primary, according to a newspaper poll published Sunday. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> held a 43 percent to 35 percent lead over <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> among voters who said they would vote for, or leaned toward, a <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> candidate if the primary had been held at the time of the poll, The <ORGANIZATION> Milwaukee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> reported in its Sunday editions. In a poll two weeks earlier, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> led <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> by 38 percent to 30 percent, the newspaper reported. Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, made the largest gain in the two-week period between polls, increasing his support from 10 percent to 15 percent, the newspaper said. Despite campaigning heavily in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> slipped from 11 percent support to 5 percent in the two weeks, the newspaper said. <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> has pinned his fading presidential prospects on <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, hoping that a victory in the primary would give him a boost going into next week's primary in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. On the Republican side, the poll showed Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would easily defeat his remaining primary challenger, former television evangelist <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> but might have a difficult time winning <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> in the general election if <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> were the Democratic nominee. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> held an 80 percent to 7 percent lead over <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>, the poll showed. However, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> ended in a virtual tie among voters who were asked which of the two they would likely vote for in the general election in November. In similar matchups, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> held a 5 point lead over <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> and a 14 point lead over <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, the newspaper said. The poll was conducted Wednesday and Thursday and was based on interviews with 845 randomly-selected <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> adults who said they were absolutely or fairly certain to vote in the primary, the newspaper said. The margin of error was plus or minus 5 percentage points. The <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> primary is expected to draw a large voter turnout with as many as 1.6 million voters or 45 percent of the eligible voters participating, state <ORGANIZATION> Elections </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> officials said.
