<HEAD>Impeachment Verdict Won't End Arizona's Legal Morass</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 This week's expected verdict in Gov. <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s impeachment trial wo n't necessarily end the legal morass that surrounds the <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> governorship. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> plans to vote Monday or Tuesday on whether <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, a first-term Republican, should be the first <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> governor removed from office. Senators heard five weeks of testimony on allegations that <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> misused $ 80,000 in state money by loaning it to his auto dealership, and that he tried to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat by a state official. With 20 of the 30 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> votes required for conviction, nobody is predicting what will happen. If he is acquitted, <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> will automatically regain the gubernatorial powers he gave up to Acting Gov. <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> secretary of <ORGANIZATION> state </ORGANIZATION>, when he was impeached by the House Feb. 5. If the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> convicts him on either count, <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> will be removed from office immediately. In either event, the matter wo n't necessarily end there. If acquitted, <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> faces two more battles to keep the governorship. A criminal trial is due to start April 21 on a charge similar to one impeachment charge the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> dropped: failure to report a $ 350,000 campaign loan. The governor faces six felony counts of fraud, perjury and filing false documents, and his brother and 1986 campaign treasurer, <PERSON> Willard </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, faces three similar counts. Senators who voted to drop the impeachment count said they feared that if they heard evidence on the charge it would jeopardize <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s right to a fair trial. If convicted in the criminal trial, <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> would be removed from office automatically and could face up to 22 years in prison. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> also is running against six candidates in a recall election May 17. Polls vary widely, with some showing him far behind but one putting <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> and Mrs. Mofford in a dead heat for first place. If the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> votes to oust him, the governor and his defense attorney, <PERSON> Jerris </PERSON> <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON>, say they could appeal to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on grounds that <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s constitutional rights were violated. It's also unclear whether the May 17 recall must be held if the state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> convicts <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> on the impeachment charges. Attorney General <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON>, a Republican, said Friday he believes the recall still must be held because the <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Constitution </ORGANIZATION> says a recall is aimed at the office, not the officeholder. However, <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON> said he philosophically opposes holding the recall if <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> has already been removed. `` I do n't think our founding fathers who drafted the Constitution ever dreamed we would be in this position,'' he said. This and other remaining legal questions should be settled in court, <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON> said. If the recall were to go ahead following a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> conviction, officials say it's also unclear whether <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> would be allowed to run. He has an automatic spot on the ballot, but <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Bender </PERSON>, dean of the <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> law school, argues that a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> vote to remove him would apply to the entire four-year term and he could not remain in office even if he won the recall vote. Legal questions surround Mrs. <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON>'s gubernatorial candidacy too. A campaign was formed to draft her because <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>'s `` resign to run'' law apparently would require her to quit as acting governor and secretary of state if she declared her candidacy. A court challenge has been mounted to see if the Mofford draft campaign was handled properly, without any involvement by the intended candidate. <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON> said his office warned years ago that the laws were unclear and should be straightened out, `` and nobody has, so here we are.''
