<HEAD>Spring Break at Easter: Beer and Bibles Co-Exist at Beach</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Operation Sonshine in 4th graf is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 While suds, sun and sin may prevail among much of the spring break throngs on the wide beaches of <LOCATION> Daytona </LOCATION> this Easter weekend, morning devotions replace hangovers in at least three beach hotels. <LOCATION> Daytona </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> has become a mecca for spring break in recent years, and an estimated 500,000 students descend on the area to forget classwork and laze in the sun. But it's not all rowdy parties and promiscuity. At the beachfront <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caribe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION>, students carry Bibles through the lobby. The hotel caters to members of the Campus Crusade for Christ, a national interdenominational group. `` You can only get so drunk and sunburned and bored,'' said <PERSON> Cliff </PERSON> <PERSON> Mills </PERSON>, director of Operation Sonshine of the Campus Crusade. `` A lot of them want to know more about Christ.'' <PERSON> Mills </PERSON>, whose organization has conducted conferences for some 3,000 students during spring break, said Campus Crusade members take their Gospel message to the beach in the afternoons and that sun worshipers are often receptive. <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Caribe </PERSON> does not allow unchaperoned non-member students under 21 to rent rooms during spring break. `` The difference is day and night,'' said <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caribe </ORGANIZATION> owner <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>, explaining how students in her hotel act compared with students staying at the dozens of other beach hotels. Ms. <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> said the biggest problem in her hotel is minor noise making, and that the students are generally well-behaved and polite. The situation was much the same at The Desert Inn and the High Seas Motel, also spring break gathering places for Campus Crusade members. `` There was no muss, no fuss and no beer-bottle throwing,'' said <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Madorsky </PERSON>, a part-owner of the Desert Inn, the Voyager and Americana hotels. Many of the crowds at <LOCATION> Daytona </LOCATION> used to go to <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION> before that community began to try to change its image with stricter law enforcement. Officials in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION> have estimated their crowds will range between 100,000 and 200,000 this year, compared with 350,000 in 1985. <LOCATION> Daytona </LOCATION> officials say this spring break, students generally have behaved better than in the past, when hotel guests tossed such objects as unopened beer cans, room chairs and even rollaway beds from balconies. So far this year, there have been two spring break fatalities in <LOCATION> Daytona </LOCATION>, one a 24-year-old man, not a student, who fell from a balcony, the other a 21-year-old student who was hit by a car. There were five other balcony falls this year in <LOCATION> Daytona </LOCATION>, but only two of the six involved students and most resulted in only minor injuries. In the past three years, six deaths have resulted from balcony accidents. In the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Panhandle </LOCATION>, two spring break visitors were hospitalized after balcony falls Friday in <LOCATION> Destin </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> resort town. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jeffers </PERSON>, 26, of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, fell while doing pullups from a fifth-floor balcony railing, authorities said. He was listed in guarded condition at <ORGANIZATION> Humana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Walton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> McGee </PERSON>, 18, of <ORGANIZATION> Baton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, who fell three floors, was in stable condition at the same hospital. <PERSON> Evelyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Fine </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Mid-Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daytona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beach </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, said some 500,000 students have come to <LOCATION> Daytona </LOCATION> for spring break this year and 330,000 will have lodged in a hotel for an average stay of about five days. She predicted that each student spends an average of $ 375, not including transportation, for a direct-dollar impact of $ 123.7 million on the <LOCATION> Daytona </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> economy.
