<HEAD>Panama's Easter Joy Dampened by Crisis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts 2d graf to clarify that packets contained incense</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The incense vendor accepted a poor woman's coins and spooned tiny measures of powdered red sandalwood, honey-crystal myrrh and dried rosemary into scraps of paper. `` Thirty cents,'' lamented <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Valencia </PERSON>, appraising the three dimes paid for the incense. `` This is the worst year ever.'' The tall, ebony-skinned man, who peddles crosses and other piety objects, said he has sold only a $ 1 portrait of Jesus Christ since midweek. Holy Week is usually the best time of year for <ORGANIZATION> Valencia </ORGANIZATION> and the small business he runs from a rickety stand in front of the Metropolitan Cathedral. Indeed, the Easter holiday usually brings joy throughout this country where about 95 percent of 2.2 million people are <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION>. But an economic and social crisis over the rule of military chief Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> has cast a pall over this year's celebration Gen. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, under drug-trafficking charges in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, has moved to consolidate control despite increasing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> pressure on him to step down and leave the country. He closed banks a month ago to prevent a cash panic after <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> froze Panamanian assets in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The government has failed to pay most of its 130,000 workers, and private employees have nowhere to cash their checks. The money crisis worsened nationwide hunger and unemployment. Meanwhile, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government has been stepping up its military presence in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, though administration officials say they do n't intend to use force to oust the strongman they once backed Another 1,300 military personnel will arrive Tuesday, bringing to nearly 12,000 the number of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops there. The administration says the troops are intended to protect <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bases and 45,000 Americans living in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. `` Never have we Panamanians lived a Lent with such tension, division and increasing want in great sectors of the country,'' said a Catholic church statement. `` The people suffer and await the Feast of the Resurrection, that it may signal some light of hope.'' Few Panamanians saw cause for optimism. The church said Saturday that opposition leaders had accepted a church role as mediator in the country's travail. But the opposition continued to demand that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> leave the country, something he has doggedly refused to do. Many people in the streets expressed despair over unremitting price increases and hunger. Fresh fish, a typical Easter meal in years past, has risen beyond modest means in this isthmus between the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> oceans. Many hunkered down in the capital of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, forgoing customary visits with family in the provinces to protect diminishing savings. <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> agent <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Chacon </PERSON> said outbound traffic through <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chorrera </LOCATION>, the main gate to the countryside, was extremely light all week. External calm replaced weeks of political activity and demonstrations in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Police replaced the heavily armed <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> soldiers on the street Friday for the first time since an unsuccessful March 16 coup attempt against <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. Five men conversed on 17th Street downtown. Two sat on a workshop bench carried out to the sidewalk and three others stood while all sipped a mixture of rum, milk and ice from paper cups. `` None of us would be here now if it were n't for the crisis,'' said a man in a sleeveless T-shirt and shorts. `` We'd be in <LOCATION> Chiriqui </LOCATION> where it's cool.'' The mountainous western province is a favorite tourist spot in better times. `` So our recreation is conversation and a couple drinks,'' said another in a blue `` guayabera,'' the loose-fitting tropical shirt. Inevitably, talk turned to the crisis. All five said they opposed <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. One suggested that `` out of the 2 million Panamanians, 200 support him.'' Because of fear of reprisals, none wanted his name published. Some of the men also talked bitterly of how <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sanctions were making their holiday and their lives difficult. `` <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> has been a good friend to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for more than 80 years,'' said one. `` And it hurts more to be wounded by a friend.'' And all doubted that the population, stymied by government repression, could do much to change things after the holiday.
