<HEAD>Even the Dullest Can Relate to Humor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST LAFAYETTE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> J.D </PERSON>. `` Dull'' <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>, self-proclaimed leader of <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dull </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Folks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unlimited </ORGANIZATION>, crashed the seventh annual National Humor Conference Saturday to panhandle for his mythical presidential candidacy. <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>, a statistical analyst from <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, became the champion of dullards everywhere with the creation of <LOCATION> DENSA </LOCATION>, an organization whose name stands for nothing except as a send-up of the high-IQ society, Mensa. Talking to a roomful of professors gathered at <ORGANIZATION> Purdue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> for a serious study of humor in American society, <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> made his money pitch: `` I said I'm in room 228 in the Union Club. You can just leave your $ 250 checks ouside the door. I have n't seen any yet.'' <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> is actually a registered participant and welcome, said <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Nilsen </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> professor. <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>'s kind of self-deprecating humor won a nod of appreciation from the professors. `` It's funny because it's a reversal,'' said <PERSON> Nilsen </PERSON>. `` It's an opposite of expectations. Whatever our frustrations are, we have ways of dealing with those frustrations by using this kind of humor.'' It's more sophisticated than one-liner humor that commonly targets ethnic groups, politicians or sex, he said. `` It's a coping device,'' he said. `` You have to develop coping devices for the real problems of the world.'' Another researcher, <PERSON> Rhoda </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>'s style has lot in common with many successful professional comedians. Despite success and the admiration of the audience, genuine self-doubt remains, she explained. `` In fact, most comedians come across as being down and up at the same time,'' she said. `` They tell us they're silly, but we secretly know they are special and brave and doing something most of us would not have the fortitude to attempt.'' The four-day humor conference, attended by about 70 professors from a variety of disciplines, runs through Monday. Studies will be presented on humor and business management, the humor of intentional mispronunciation, and a paper titled, `` The Continuing Saga of <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>'s Governor: A Humorous Sequel.''
