<HEAD>President Extends State of Emergency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> on Saturday extended a state of emergency in an important mining region where leftist guerrillas have repeatedly attacked mines and railroads. A decree in the official gazette, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peruano </LOCATION>, said the emergency measures would be extended for another two months across the mountainous eastern half of <LOCATION> Pasco </LOCATION> state. Cerro de Pasco, the state capital, is 120 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>. Pasco is the center of <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s vital mining industry that provides more than 50 percent of the nation's foreign exchange. Maoist Shining Path guerrillas have made hundreds of attacks in the zone in an effort to cripple <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s economy. The government began decreeing states of emergency in November 1980 because of the insurgency. Parts of seven states, including <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, currently are under states of emergency. A state of emergency suspends citizens' rights to travel and assemble freely and permits government forces to conduct searches without warrants and hold suspects for lengthy periods without filing charges. The government says more than 10,000 people have been killed in violence related to the Shining Path's eight-year-old campaign to gain power.
