<HEAD>Opposition Party Votes To Merge With Government Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANGUS SHAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The party of former opposition leader <PERSON> Joshua </PERSON> <PERSON> Nkomo </PERSON> voted Saturday to merge with the ruling party of Prime Minister <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON> in a step to unite the nation's most powerful political movements. <PERSON> Nkomo </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Zimbabwe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, opened the party's one-day congress with a plea to more than 5,000 delegates to endorse a unity accord he signed with <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON> on Dec. 23. <PERSON> Nkomo </PERSON> said, `` This accord opens up broad vistas for the economy of the country through the participation of all the people in development.'' <PERSON> Nkomo </PERSON>, 70, needed a simple majority vote to endorse the merger but the <ORGANIZATION> congress </ORGANIZATION> passed two resolutions by unanimous vote. The resolutions approved the merger and asked <PERSON> Nkomo </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON> to proceed with uniting their parties' structures under one banner, effectively dismantling <PERSON> Nkomo </PERSON>'s party. `` This country will owe a lot to your decisions,'' <PERSON> Nkomo </PERSON> said after the vote. `` We have a collective vision. We must stand together. We must not deceive each other.'' <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Zimbabwe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> is to vote on the unity accord on April 9. <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nkomo </PERSON> originally were allies in the campaign to bring majority black rule to the country that was the white-ruled British colony of <LOCATION> Rhodesia </LOCATION>. In 1963, <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON> and some other officials left <PERSON> Nkomo </PERSON>'s party to form their own leftist movement. Both parties were outlawed by then-Prime Minister <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>'s white-dominated government in 1964 <PERSON> Nkomo </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON>, along with hundreds of other black nationalists, were detained for more than a decade. <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nkomo </PERSON> then became leaders in a seven-year guerrilla war that ended when the country became independent on April 18, 1980. The alliance <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nkomo </PERSON> had formed during the war came apart after <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON>'s party won <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>'s first election after independence. <PERSON> Nkomo </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON> remained political foes until Dec. 23, when they signed the unity accord that signaled an end to frequent fighting between their supporters. In January <PERSON> Nkomo </PERSON> was appointed one of three senior <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> ministers in a government shuffle. If both parties approve the merger, <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON>, 64, will have the support of all but one legislator in the 100-seat <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> and the 40-member <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. He needs the vote of all 140 lawmakers to change the constitution and establish a one-party socialist state that he advocates. The dissident lawmaker is businessman <PERSON> Goodson </PERSON> <PERSON> Sithole </PERSON>, but political observers say he could join <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON>'s party before a vote is taken in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> later this year. In another development, a gang of men stabbed to death a white Zimbabwean farmer at his home and beat his wife unconscious, police reported Saturday. They said the body of <PERSON> Johannes </PERSON> <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Toit </PERSON>, 55, was found by the family cook Friday in the farmhouse near the town of <LOCATION> Karoi </LOCATION>, 112 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Harare </LOCATION>. Police said they had not determined the motive, but neighbors who spoke on condition of anonymity said <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Toit </PERSON> recently had argued with some of his black employees.
