<HEAD>Robeson County Indians Write Letter To Soviet Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAYETTEVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two Robeson County Indians charged in the armed takeover of a <LOCATION> Lumberton </LOCATION> newspaper said they have written to Soviet General Secretary <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. The letters will be delivered to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> by attorney <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Kunstler </PERSON>, who hopes to make Indian rights an issue at the May summit between <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatcher </PERSON> on Saturday. <PERSON> Hatcher </PERSON>, 30, and <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON>, 19, both of <LOCATION> Pembroke </LOCATION>, are charged with hostage-taking and the manufacture and possession of illegal weapons in connection with the Feb. 1 siege of The Robesonian newspaper in <LOCATION> Lumberton </LOCATION>. `` We raised several issues in our letters regarding the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration and past administrations' treatment of native Americans that has been brought about by lies and broken treaties,'' <PERSON> Hatcher </PERSON> said in a telephone interview with the <ORGANIZATION> Fayetteville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Observer-Times </ORGANIZATION>. `` We are political prisoners, and we raise the fact that there are many other political prisoners like us.'' <PERSON> Hatcher </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON>, both <ORGANIZATION> Tuscarora </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION>, have said that mistreatment of minorities in <LOCATION> Robeson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> led them to take over the newspaper offices. They released their hostages eight hours after the siege began following a commitment by Gov. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> to appoint a task force to study the <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION>' claims agains the <LOCATION> Robeson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> government and law enforcement agencies.
