<HEAD>Administration Lowers Rhetoric, Expectations in Central America</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 11th graf pvs bgng, `The official,' with 3 grafs and
penultimate graf pvs bgng, `Talks on,' with 1 graf to UPDATE with
Contras delaying scheduled Wednesday start of negotiations</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA </BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The guns are silent for the time being in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and there is even a truce of sorts between Republicans and Democrats on the contentious issue of aid to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels. And as <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s leftist government and the U.S.-backed rebels prepare to negotiate a settlement to end their six-year war, the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has remained uncharacteristically silent, no longer using apocalyptic terms to discuss its perception of the stakes involved. Along with its rhetoric, the administration is lowering its expectations of its ability to influence events in the region. But most officials believe the Sandinista government is going into the peace talks in a commanding position because of Contra military weakness. For now, almost everyone, from the Sandinista government to administration and congressional hardliners, believes the peace process should be allowed to go forward without guns ablaze. Just a few weeks ago, bipartisanship on the Contra aid issue seemed beyond reach. An administration aid proposal was defeated narrowly in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on Feb. 3 and a substitute Democratic plan also was rejected by a slim margin a few weeks later. But this past week, both houses of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> overwhelmingly approved a $ 48 million package providing humanitarian aid for the Contras as well as for children on both sides who have been injured in the conflict. The package includes $ 10 million for independent verification of the cease-fire agreement. Following Contra acquiescence to a 60-day cease-fire on March 23, both Republicans and Democrats agreed that this type of aid package was the only option available to them. But the legislation also includes a promise by House Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, that he will not block `` fair and orderly'' consideration of a new military aid request if the peace talks collapse due to Sandinista intransigence. Sen. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>, D-Conn., noted that the aid bill did not provide weapons for the rebels, as Contra supporters had hoped And it went too far for Contra opponents, who object to sending any aid. `` This package strikes a balance,'' <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON> said during an unusually harmonious floor debate on the proposal last Thursday. <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON> said the sole purpose of the package is to support the cease-fire agreement: `` If not for that agreement, we would n't be doing this today.'' The official administration line is that the temporary cease-fire was a step forward, and it is now up to the disputants to resolve their differences at the bargaining table when peace talks begin. Those talks were scheduled to begin Wednesday, but the Contras said Saturday they would delay the talks for one week to provide more time for technical commissions of both sides to work out details of the five zones inside <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> where rebel forces are to gather under the provisions of the cease-fire accord. But a government statement signed Saturday by Deputy Foreign Minister <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> <PERSON> Tinoco </PERSON> stressed it was `` extremely important'' to comply with the cease-fire pact's timetable and stick by the April 6 meeting date. The administration's low-key attitude was symbolized by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s decision on Friday to sign the aid legislation in his White House residence, forgoing the ceremonial fanfare that attends some bill-signings. The administration has long contended that the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> will be forced to democratize and demilitarize only through Contra military pressure, or at least the threat of it. Just last February, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said the Sandinista government `` will be free to continue the consolidation of their totalitarian regime, the military buildup inside <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and communist subversion of their neighbors'' if military aid to the Contras stops. The administration has not renounced <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s grim prediction but it appears that an informal moratorium has been placed on that type of rhetoric. Things have been quiet in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> as well. A formal cease-fire replaced the temporary one on Friday, and the <ORGANIZATION> Nicaraguan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> reported no violations. Many Nicaraguans marked the long Easter weekend by taking vacations at beaches on the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> coast. Banks, government offices, stores and most restaurants were closed until Monday. When talks on a permanent truce begin, the Contras are expected to issue demands for 17 democratic reforms, abolition of the draft, the repatriation Soviet bloc military advisers and other measures. In effect, they will be asking the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> to negotiate the revolution, something the government has said it would never do. The process is not expected to be free of friction.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Gedda </PERSON> has covered foreign affairs for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> since 1968.
</TEXT>
