<HEAD>Eleven Protesters Arrested at Public Housing Project</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police arrested 11 protesters who moved into vacant apartments at a public housing project Saturday, but did not arrest demonstrators who set up a nearby tent city, officials said. The 11 who were arrested at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Horner </PERSON> <PERSON> Homes </PERSON> were charged with criminal trespass and released on $ 100 bond apiece, said Officer <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Touhy </PERSON> He said police were called to the buildings by housing authority security guards. The protesters were members of the Chicago-Gary Area Union of the Homeless, and moved into the vacant apartments as part of a two-pronged demonstration on behalf of the city's estimated 25,000 homeless. The other half of the demonstration involved setting up a dozen tents on a vacant lot nearby. Union members vowed to stay in the tents for a week, saying they wanted to call attention to the housing authority's refusal to allow the homeless to stay in its vacant apartments. Several members of the union said they would try to move back into the apartments where the 11 were arrested. <PERSON> Dolores </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, a secretary for the union, said this weekend was chosen for the protest because April 1 is the date that half of the city-run shelters and warming centers for the homeless were closed this year. She estimated that about 500 people had to go back on the streets because of the seasonal move.
